{"title_page": "Dan Carden", "text_new": "{{short description|British Labour politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Dan Carden\n| honorific-suffix    = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| office              = [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Development]]\n| leader              = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| predecessor         = [[Kate Osamor]]\n| successor           = [[Preet Gill]]\n| term_start          = 1 December 2018\n| term_end            = 6 April 2020\n| office1             = [[Department for International Development|Shadow Minister for International Development]]\n| leader1             = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start1         = 12 January 2018\n| term_end1           = 1 December 2018\n| predecessor1        = [[Roberta Blackman-Woods]]\n| successor1          = [[Preet Gill]]\n| office2             = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Liverpool Walton (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Walton]]\n| image               = [[File:Official portrait of Dan Carden MP crop 2.jpg|frameless|]]\n| caption             = Carden in 2019\n| party               = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| majority2           = 30,520 (74.8%)\n| predecessor2        = [[Steve Rotheram]]\n| successor2          = \n| birth_name          = Daniel Joseph Carden<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=61961 |date=19 June 2017 |page=11778}}</ref>\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1986|10|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = Liverpool, England\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| alma_mater          = [[London School of Economics]]\n| term_start2         = 8 June 2017\n| term_end2           = \n| website             = {{URL|facebook.com/DanCardenMP/}}\n}}\n\n'''Daniel Joseph Carden''' (born 28 October 1986) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] [[politician]] serving as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Liverpool Walton (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Walton]] since [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]].<ref name=\"liverpoolecho1\">{{cite web|first=Liam |last=Thorp |url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/meet-30-year-old-who-13021671 |title=We meet the 30-year-old who beat Mayor Anderson to contest Liverpool MP role |work=Liverpool Echo |date=11 May 2017 |accessdate=8 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nCarden has described himself as a \"proud [[Scouse]]r\", having been born and raised in [[Liverpool]]. His mother worked in the [[National Health Service|NHS]] for over 40 years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.leftfutures.org/2017/05/trade-unionist-dan-carden-selected-in-liverpool-walton/|title=Trade unionist Dan Carden selected in Liverpool Walton|last=|first=|date=10 May 2017|work=Left Futures|accessdate=10 June 2017}}</ref> His father, Mike Carden, was the shop steward during the [[Liverpool dockers' dispute (1995\u201398)|Liverpool dockers' dispute]] during the 1990s, and was left unemployed for seven years after being sacked for refusing to cross a picket line. In his maiden speech, Carden recalled: \u201cFrom the age of eight, I stood on picket lines, and I\u2019m as proud to stand alongside workers in struggle today as an MP as I was then as a kid\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rZdae0Yw8Kg|title=Dan Carden, maiden speech (full)|date=13 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nHis secondary education was at [[St Edward's College]] in [[West Derby]] (OE 1998\u20132005) where he was the Head Boy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.st-edwards.co.uk/alumni/alumni-news/150517-oe-daniel-carden-appointed-mp/|title=Secondary education|last=|first=|date=|website=|accessdate=}}</ref> He went on to study BSc International Relations at the [[London School of Economics]], where he was also Chair of the University [[Labour Students|Labour Club]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.getintothis.co.uk/2018/10/dan-carden-mp-talks-parliament-jeremy-corbyn-and-music-venue-closures/|title=Dan Carden MP talks Parliament, Jeremy Corbyn and music venue closures|work=Getintothis|date=22 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrior to becoming an MP, Carden worked as a [[Caseworker (politics)|caseworker]] and with [[Len McCluskey]] at [[Unite the Union|Unite]].\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nIn 2017, Carden defeated Liverpool City Mayor [[Joe Anderson (politician)|Joe Anderson]], [[Theresa Griffin]] MEP and other prominent local figures to be selected by the [[National Executive Committee|NEC]] to become Labour's candidate for [[Liverpool Walton (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Walton]], after the previous MP [[Steve Rotheram]] stood down to become [[Metro Mayor of the Liverpool City Region|Liverpool City Region Metro Mayor]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/liverpools-new-mp-dan-carden-13160089|title=Liverpool's new MP Dan Carden 'absolutely honoured'|last=Thomas|first=Joe|date=9 June 2017|work=Liverpool Echo|accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref> On 8 June, he was elected MP with 85.7% of the vote with a 32,551 majority \u2013 the strongest result in the seat's history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://electionresults.parliament.uk/election/2017-06-08/results/Location/Constituency/Liverpool%2C%20Walton|title=Liverpool, Walton - 2017 Election Results|website=General Elections Online|accessdate=20 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nAn avowed [[socialism|socialist]], he has been compared to his predecessor [[Eric Heffer]], who he paid tribute to in a memorial lecture in January 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribunemag.co.uk/2019/01/never-a-yes-man/|title=Never a Yes Man|website=Tribune|last=Carden|first=Dan|date=27 January 2019}}</ref> He is a patron of [[LGBT Labour]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lgbtlabour.org.uk/patrons|title=Patrons|website=LGBT+ Labour}}</ref> and a member of the [[Socialist Campaign Group]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DanCardenMP/status/1075738393919873024|title=Last night @jeremycorbyn visited our Socialist Campaign Group meeting in the same room he was nominated to stand for Leader of the Labour Party.|first=Dan Carden|last=MP|date=20 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nCarden successfully defended his Liverpool Walton seat in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 General Election]], winning 34,538 votes. This represented 84.7% of the vote.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000794|title=Liverpool Walton parliamentary constituency - Election 2019|website=BBC News|accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Shadow International Development Secretary===\nOn 1 December 2018, he was appointed [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Development]] after the resignation of [[Kate Osamor]] following events surrounding her son's drugs conviction.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2018/12/labour-mp-kate-osamor-resigns-shadow-international-development-secretary|title=Labour MP Kate Osamor resigns as shadow international development secretary|last=|first=|date=1 December 2018|work=New Statesman|accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the run-up to the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 General Election]], Carden promised \u201cthe most radical international development policies ever seen in this country.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DanCardenMP/status/1197485575453970433|title=I'm proud of our section of the #LabourManifesto, with the most radical international development policies ever seen in this country...|first=Dan Carden|last=MP|date=21 November 2019}}</ref> He said Labour would turn the [[CDC Group]] into a green development bank<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2019/nov/21/labour-vows-to-make-uk-development-bank-a-champion-of-climate-justice|title=Labour vows to make UK development bank a champion of climate justice|last=McVeigh|first=Karen|date=21 November 2019|work=The Guardian|accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> and create a new Public Services Unit for water, healthcare and education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fabians.org.uk/people-not-profit/|title=People, not profit|last=Carden|first=Dan|date=7 August 2019|work=Fabians|accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> Other policy plans included banning all aid spending on fossil fuels, support for trade unions globally, tripling funding for women\u2019s rights groups, introducing an ombudsman for abuse in aid sector and support for small-scale farmers with a Food Sovereignty Fund.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://labour.org.uk/manifesto/a-new-internationalism/|title=2019 Labour Manifesto|website=The Labour Party}}</ref>\n\nCarden called for the UK to use its influence to democratise the [[International Monetary Fund|IMF]] and [[World Bank]], challenging the agenda of liberalising markets, cutting social spending and privatising public services \u201cso the poorest countries can decide their own destiny\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DanCardenMP/status/1116371840409186305|title=To end global poverty we must change the rules of a failed economic system...|first=Dan Carden|last=MP|date=11 April 2019}}</ref> Alongside Shadow Chancellor [[John McDonnell]], he proposed an Overseas Loan Transparency Act to establish a new compulsory register to put an end to exploitative secret loans to foreign governments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://guce.huffingtonpost.co.uk/copyConsent?sessionId=3_cc-session_2fc5b499-4514-4b13-a572-34fae167a3b1&inline=false&lang=en-gb|title=A Labour Government Will Not Ignore The Global Debt Crisis|date=17 June 2019|work=Huffington Post UK|accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCarden is gay.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/gay-liverpool-mp-skewers-esther-16358214|title=Gay Liverpool MP's perfect reply to Esther McVey's LGBT school comments|journal=Liverpool Echo|first=Liam|last=Thorp|date=31 May 2019|accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref> He is a supporter of [[Liverpool F.C.]] and an advocate of football fan activism, including Liverpool and [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] supporters' initiative Fans Supporting Foodbanks.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/fans-foodbank-support-shows-best-13659654|title=Foodbank support shows 'best of Scousers'|last=Johnson|first=Mark|date=22 September 2017|work=Liverpool Echo|accessdate=18 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Facebook | DanCardenMP | Dan Carden}}\n*{{Twitter}}\n*{{Official website|66prioryroad.co.uk}}\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=dan-carden/4651 |publicwhip=Dan_Carden |theywork=dan_carden}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Steve Rotheram]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n |title=Member of Parliament for [[Liverpool Walton (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Walton]]\n |years=[[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]]\u2013present\n}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{North West Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carden, Dan}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from West Derby]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:People educated at St Edward's College]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from England]]\n[[Category:LGBT members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:English socialists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Labour politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Dan Carden\n| honorific-suffix    = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| office              = [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Development]]\n| leader              = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| predecessor         = [[Kate Osamor]]\n| successor           = [[Preet Gill]]\n| term_start          = 1 December 2018\n| term_end            = 6 April 2020\n| office1             = [[Department for International Development|Shadow Minister for International Development]]\n| leader1             = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start1         = 12 January 2018\n| term_end1           = 1 December 2018\n| predecessor1        = [[Roberta Blackman-Woods]]\n| successor1          = [[Preet Gill]]\n| office2             = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Liverpool Walton (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Walton]]\n| image               = [[File:Official portrait of Dan Carden MP crop 2.jpg|frameless|]]\n| caption             = Carden in 2019\n| party               = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| majority2           = 30,520 (74.8%)\n| predecessor2        = [[Steve Rotheram]]\n| successor2          = \n| birth_name          = Daniel Joseph Carden<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=61961 |date=19 June 2017 |page=11778}}</ref>\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1986|10|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = Liverpool, England\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| alma_mater          = [[London School of Economics]]\n| term_start2         = 8 June 2017\n| term_end2           = \n| website             = {{URL|facebook.com/DanCardenMP/}}\n}}\n\n'''Daniel Joseph Carden''' (born 28 October 1986) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] [[politician]] serving as as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Liverpool Walton (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Walton]] since [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]].<ref name=\"liverpoolecho1\">{{cite web|first=Liam |last=Thorp |url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/meet-30-year-old-who-13021671 |title=We meet the 30-year-old who beat Mayor Anderson to contest Liverpool MP role |work=Liverpool Echo |date=11 May 2017 |accessdate=8 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nCarden has described himself as a \"proud [[Scouse]]r\", having been born and raised in [[Liverpool]]. His mother worked in the [[National Health Service|NHS]] for over 40 years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.leftfutures.org/2017/05/trade-unionist-dan-carden-selected-in-liverpool-walton/|title=Trade unionist Dan Carden selected in Liverpool Walton|last=|first=|date=10 May 2017|work=Left Futures|accessdate=10 June 2017}}</ref> His father, Mike Carden, was the shop steward during the [[Liverpool dockers' dispute (1995\u201398)|Liverpool dockers' dispute]] during the 1990s, and was left unemployed for seven years after being sacked for refusing to cross a picket line. In his maiden speech, Carden recalled: \u201cFrom the age of eight, I stood on picket lines, and I\u2019m as proud to stand alongside workers in struggle today as an MP as I was then as a kid\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rZdae0Yw8Kg|title=Dan Carden, maiden speech (full)|date=13 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nHis secondary education was at [[St Edward's College]] in [[West Derby]] (OE 1998\u20132005) where he was the Head Boy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.st-edwards.co.uk/alumni/alumni-news/150517-oe-daniel-carden-appointed-mp/|title=Secondary education|last=|first=|date=|website=|accessdate=}}</ref> He went on to study BSc International Relations at the [[London School of Economics]], where he was also Chair of the University [[Labour Students|Labour Club]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.getintothis.co.uk/2018/10/dan-carden-mp-talks-parliament-jeremy-corbyn-and-music-venue-closures/|title=Dan Carden MP talks Parliament, Jeremy Corbyn and music venue closures|work=Getintothis|date=22 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrior to becoming an MP, Carden worked as a [[Caseworker (politics)|caseworker]] and with [[Len McCluskey]] at [[Unite the Union|Unite]].\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nIn 2017, Carden defeated Liverpool City Mayor [[Joe Anderson (politician)|Joe Anderson]], [[Theresa Griffin]] MEP and other prominent local figures to be selected by the [[National Executive Committee|NEC]] to become Labour's candidate for [[Liverpool Walton (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Walton]], after the previous MP [[Steve Rotheram]] stood down to become [[Metro Mayor of the Liverpool City Region|Liverpool City Region Metro Mayor]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/liverpools-new-mp-dan-carden-13160089|title=Liverpool's new MP Dan Carden 'absolutely honoured'|last=Thomas|first=Joe|date=9 June 2017|work=Liverpool Echo|accessdate=9 June 2017}}</ref> On 8 June, he was elected MP with 85.7% of the vote with a 32,551 majority \u2013 the strongest result in the seat's history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://electionresults.parliament.uk/election/2017-06-08/results/Location/Constituency/Liverpool%2C%20Walton|title=Liverpool, Walton - 2017 Election Results|website=General Elections Online|accessdate=20 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nAn avowed [[socialism|socialist]], he has been compared to his predecessor [[Eric Heffer]], who he paid tribute to in a memorial lecture in January 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribunemag.co.uk/2019/01/never-a-yes-man/|title=Never a Yes Man|website=Tribune|last=Carden|first=Dan|date=27 January 2019}}</ref> He is a patron of [[LGBT Labour]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lgbtlabour.org.uk/patrons|title=Patrons|website=LGBT+ Labour}}</ref> and a member of the [[Socialist Campaign Group]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DanCardenMP/status/1075738393919873024|title=Last night @jeremycorbyn visited our Socialist Campaign Group meeting in the same room he was nominated to stand for Leader of the Labour Party.|first=Dan Carden|last=MP|date=20 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nCarden successfully defended his Liverpool Walton seat in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 General Election]], winning 34,538 votes. This represented 84.7% of the vote.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000794|title=Liverpool Walton parliamentary constituency - Election 2019|website=BBC News|accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Shadow International Development Secretary===\nOn 1 December 2018, he was appointed [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Development]] after the resignation of [[Kate Osamor]] following events surrounding her son's drugs conviction.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2018/12/labour-mp-kate-osamor-resigns-shadow-international-development-secretary|title=Labour MP Kate Osamor resigns as shadow international development secretary|last=|first=|date=1 December 2018|work=New Statesman|accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the run-up to the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 General Election]], Carden promised \u201cthe most radical international development policies ever seen in this country.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DanCardenMP/status/1197485575453970433|title=I'm proud of our section of the #LabourManifesto, with the most radical international development policies ever seen in this country...|first=Dan Carden|last=MP|date=21 November 2019}}</ref> He said Labour would turn the [[CDC Group]] into a green development bank<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2019/nov/21/labour-vows-to-make-uk-development-bank-a-champion-of-climate-justice|title=Labour vows to make UK development bank a champion of climate justice|last=McVeigh|first=Karen|date=21 November 2019|work=The Guardian|accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> and create a new Public Services Unit for water, healthcare and education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fabians.org.uk/people-not-profit/|title=People, not profit|last=Carden|first=Dan|date=7 August 2019|work=Fabians|accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref> Other policy plans included banning all aid spending on fossil fuels, support for trade unions globally, tripling funding for women\u2019s rights groups, introducing an ombudsman for abuse in aid sector and support for small-scale farmers with a Food Sovereignty Fund.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://labour.org.uk/manifesto/a-new-internationalism/|title=2019 Labour Manifesto|website=The Labour Party}}</ref>\n\nCarden called for the UK to use its influence to democratise the [[International Monetary Fund|IMF]] and [[World Bank]], challenging the agenda of liberalising markets, cutting social spending and privatising public services \u201cso the poorest countries can decide their own destiny\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DanCardenMP/status/1116371840409186305|title=To end global poverty we must change the rules of a failed economic system...|first=Dan Carden|last=MP|date=11 April 2019}}</ref> Alongside Shadow Chancellor [[John McDonnell]], he proposed an Overseas Loan Transparency Act to establish a new compulsory register to put an end to exploitative secret loans to foreign governments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://guce.huffingtonpost.co.uk/copyConsent?sessionId=3_cc-session_2fc5b499-4514-4b13-a572-34fae167a3b1&inline=false&lang=en-gb|title=A Labour Government Will Not Ignore The Global Debt Crisis|date=17 June 2019|work=Huffington Post UK|accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCarden is gay.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/gay-liverpool-mp-skewers-esther-16358214|title=Gay Liverpool MP's perfect reply to Esther McVey's LGBT school comments|journal=Liverpool Echo|first=Liam|last=Thorp|date=31 May 2019|accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref> He is a supporter of [[Liverpool F.C.]] and an advocate of football fan activism, including Liverpool and [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] supporters' initiative Fans Supporting Foodbanks.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/fans-foodbank-support-shows-best-13659654|title=Foodbank support shows 'best of Scousers'|last=Johnson|first=Mark|date=22 September 2017|work=Liverpool Echo|accessdate=18 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Facebook | DanCardenMP | Dan Carden}}\n*{{Twitter}}\n*{{Official website|66prioryroad.co.uk}}\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=dan-carden/4651 |publicwhip=Dan_Carden |theywork=dan_carden}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Steve Rotheram]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n |title=Member of Parliament for [[Liverpool Walton (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Walton]]\n |years=[[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]]\u2013present\n}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{North West Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carden, Dan}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from West Derby]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:People educated at St Edward's College]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from England]]\n[[Category:LGBT members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:English socialists]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word reworded", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dan_Carden"}
{"title_page": "John Collinson (historian)", "text_new": "{{other uses|John Collinson (disambiguation)}}\nThe Rev. '''John Collinson''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FSA}} (19 July 1757 \u2013 27 August 1793) was an English cleric, [[antiquarian]] and [[county historian]]. He is best known for his three-volume history of [[Somerset]] which he published at the age of only 34, two years before his untimely death, and which earned him the title of 'the Somerset historian'.<ref>{{cite book |first=R. W. |last=Eyton |authorlink=Robert William Eyton |title=Domesday Studies: an analysis and digest of the Somerset survey |location=London |publisher=Reeves & Turner |year=1880 |volume=1 |pages=10, 61,113}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\n[[File:Daines_Barrington.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Daines Barrington]], who backed John Collinson for election to Fellowship of the Society of Antiquaries of London in 1784]]\n[[File:Geograph 2320613 Long Ashton Church, Bristol.jpg|thumb|upright|All Saints Church, Long Ashton, Somerset, of which Collinson became vicar in 1787]]\n[[File:Colonnade, Hotwells, Bristol.jpg|thumb|upright| Hotwells, Bristol, where John Collinson died at the age of 36 after a lingering illness on 27 August 1793.]]\nCollinson was the son of the Rev. John Collinson of [[Bromham, Wiltshire]], where he was born on 19 July 1757. He matriculated at [[Brasenose College, Oxford]] in 1775, but did not complete a degree course. He was ordained deacon in 1779 with the sponsorship of the Rev. Thomas Meyler (c.1718\u20131786), having made further studies at [[The Queen's College, Oxford]]. He was then curate to Meyler in 1780 at [[Marlborough, Wiltshire|Marlborough]].<ref name =\"ODNB\">{{cite ODNB|id=5963|first=Robert W.|last=Dunning|title=Collinson, John}}</ref><ref>{{alox2|title=Meyler, Thomas (1)}}</ref>\n\nCollinson moved to [[Cirencester]] where in 1781 he married. In 1782 he was appointed vicar of [[Clanfield, Oxfordshire]]. At this period he published one book, and issued proposals for county histories, firstly of [[Wiltshire]] and then of Somerset. He associated with the antiquarians [[Joseph Kilner]] and [[Samuel Rudder]], and in 1784 was elected a Fellow of the [[Society of Antiquaries of London]], backed by [[Daines Barrington]], [[William Boys (surgeon)|William Boys]] and [[Edward Hasted]].<ref name =\"ODNB\"/>\n\nIn 1787 Collinson became vicar of [[Long Ashton]] and perpetual curate of [[Whitchurch, Somerset|Filton]] (''alias'' [[Whitchurch, Somerset|Whitchurch]]) in Somerset. He died at [[Hotwells, Bristol]] on 27 August 1793, and was buried at Long Ashton.<ref name =\"ODNB\"/>\n\n==History of Somerset==\nCollinson's magnum opus was his ''History and Antiquities of the County of Somerset'', which bears the date 1791 on its title pages although it did not in fact appear until 1792.\n\nThe work made use of the standard antiquarian and historical works, as the title page acknowledges, and partially included a survey by [[Edmund Rack]] of [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]]. An initial difficulty was met when the expected access to the papers of [[John Strachey (geologist)|John Strachey]] was not granted. The history is neatly organised by parish and hundred.\n\nWhile the history was heavily criticised for a lack of original research in the ''[[Gentleman's Magazine]]'' on publication,<ref>{{cite journal |author=R. P. |title=Collinson's History of Somersetshire \u2013 Farley Church |journal=The Gentleman's Magazine and Historical Chronicle |volume=64 |issue=1 |date=June 1794 |pages=497\u201399 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=al7PAAAAMAAJ&printsec=titlepage&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q&f=false }}</ref> it has subsequently been widely acknowledged as an ingenious work<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Felix Farley, Bristol Journal, 31 August 1793</ref> that made substantial advances in [[Domesday Book|Domesday]] nomenclature, and contains valuable records of church monument inscriptions, many of which have since been lost.<ref name=\"index\"/> That it is in large part a skilful collation and synthesis of existing historical sources, supported by some research and a deep first-hand knowledge of the county, was acknowledged by Collinson in his introduction.<ref>John Collinson, History and Antiquities of the County of Somerset, volume 1, p ix</ref> It must be remembered that Collinson was only 24 years old when he issued proposals for the history, and only 34 years old when it was published; extensive original research was neither claimed nor could reasonably be expected.<ref name=\"index\"/>\n\nCollinson's immense, historically important achievement was freely acknowledged almost a century later by [[Robert William Eyton]] who praised the historian's topographical knowledge, scholarship, utmost precision and constancy.<ref>{{cite book |first=R. W. |last=Eyton |authorlink=Robert William Eyton |title=Domesday Studies: an analysis and digest of the Somerset survey |location=London |publisher=Reeves & Turner |year=1880 |volume=1 |page=10 }}</ref> Perhaps the greatest proof of its merit is that Collinson's work has remained the standard history of Somerset for almost two centuries, and is only now being superseded by the [[Somerset Victoria County History|''Victoria County History'' of Somerset]], still in progress, of which the published volumes reference Collinson extensively throughout.\n\nA separate index volume to Collinson's history was prepared and published by the Revs. Frederic William Weaver and E. H. Bates just over a century later in 1898, which greatly facilitates the use of the work as well as updating and standardising the spelling of place names.<ref name=\"index\">{{cite book |first1=F. W. |last1=Weaver |first2=E. H. |last2=Bates |title=Index to Collinson's History of Somerset |location=Taunton |year=1898 }}</ref>\n\n==List of works==\n* ''The Beauties of British Antiquity: selected from the writings of esteemed antiquaries with notes and observations'', 1779.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>\n* ''History and Antiquities of the County of Somerset, Collected from Authentick Records and an Actual Survey made by the late Mr Edmund Rack. Adorned with a Map of the County and Engravings of Roman and other Reliques, Town-Seals, Baths, Churches and Gentlemen's Seats'', in 3 volumes, published at Bath, Somerset, 1791:\n** Volume 1, Bath, 1791 [https://archive.org/details/historyantiqutit01colluoft]\n** Volume 2, Bath, 1791 [https://archive.org/details/historyantiqutit02colluoft]\n** Volume 3, Bath, 1791 [https://archive.org/details/historyantiqutit03colluoft]\n\n==Family==\nCollinson married Mary Hill in Cirencester on 25 March 1781.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">Gloucestershire Archives; Gloucester, Gloucestershire; Gloucestershire Church of England Parish Registers; Reference Number: P86/1 IN 1/3</ref> She died in 1787, leaving him a son John (b. 16 April 1782).<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/><ref name=\"ODNB\"/> He married as his second wife, Harriot Harris, on 7 July 1788 at [[Clifton, Bristol|Clifton]], believed to be a near relation of [[John Harris (Bristol)|John Harris]] who was a subscriber to the History of Somerset.<ref>Bristol Archives; Bristol, England; Bristol Church of England Parish Registers; Reference: P/StA/R/4/b</ref> There was no surviving issue of this marriage.\n\nCollinson died after a lingering illness<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> on 27 August 1793. In his will, made on 10 April 1793 and proved on 8 January 1798,<ref>The National Archives, PROB 11/1300/59</ref> he left all his books, manuscripts, drawings, prints, collection of coins and antiquities to his son, John Collinson, apart from the plates engraved for the History of Somerset, in the hands of bookseller [[Charles Dilly]] and in his estimation valued between two and three hundred pounds, which were left to his mother, Elizabeth Collinson. He also left a legacy to his sister, Elizabeth Collinson, of a ring and thirty pounds to be raised from the sale of the copyright of the History of Somerset. The residue of his estate was to go to his wife. However at the administration of the will in 1798, Timothy Stevens, a bookseller of Cirencester and one of the original subscribers to the History of Somerset, came forward as a creditor and was granted all of Collinson's goods and chattels.\n\nBy 1798 Collinson's widow, Harriot, had married John Francis Hamm of [[Little Chelsea]], Middlesex, who was the chief legatee of his uncle John Manning, a wealthy West Indies merchant.<ref>Vere Langford Oliver, Caribbeana, London, 1910, vol 1</ref> Harriot died at St Anne's Place, [[Cambridge Heath]], London, on 21 December 1846.<ref>The Gentleman's Magazine, Volume 27, 1847, p 215</ref><ref>London Metropolitan Archives, Church of England Parish Registers, 1813-2003, p79/jn1/132</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|John Collinson}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Collinson, John}}\n[[Category:1757 births]]\n[[Category:1793 deaths]]\n[[Category:English Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:Historians of Somerset]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Society of Antiquaries of London]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|John Collinson (disambiguation)}}\nThe Rev. '''John Collinson''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FSA}} (19 July 1757 \u2013 27 August 1793) was an English cleric, [[antiquarian]] and [[county historian]]. He is best known for his three-volume history of [[Somerset]] which he published at the age of only 34, two years before his untimely death, and which earned him the title of 'the Somerset historian'.<ref>{{cite book |first=R. W. |last=Eyton |authorlink=Robert William Eyton |title=Domesday Studies: an analysis and digest of the Somerset survey |location=London |publisher=Reeves & Turner |year=1880 |volume=1 |pages=10, 61,113}}</ref> \n\n==Life==\n[[File:Daines_Barrington.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Daines Barrington]], who backed John Collinson for election to Fellowship of the Society of Antiquaries of London in 1784]]\n[[File:Geograph 2320613 Long Ashton Church, Bristol.jpg|thumb|upright|All Saints Church, Long Ashton, Somerset, of which Collinson became vicar in 1787]]\n[[File:Colonnade, Hotwells, Bristol.jpg|thumb|upright| Hotwells, Bristol, where John Collinson died at the age of 36 after a lingering illness on 27 August 1793.]]\nCollinson was the son of the Rev. John Collinson of [[Bromham, Wiltshire]], where he was born on 19 July 1757. He matriculated at [[Brasenose College, Oxford]] in 1775, but did not complete a degree course. He was ordained deacon in 1779 with the sponsorship of the Rev. Thomas Meyler (c.1718\u20131786), having made further studies at [[The Queen's College, Oxford]]. He was then curate to Meyler in 1780 at [[Marlborough, Wiltshire|Marlborough]].<ref name =\"ODNB\">{{cite ODNB|id=5963|first=Robert W.|last=Dunning|title=Collinson, John}}</ref><ref>{{alox2|title=Meyler, Thomas (1)}}</ref>\n\nCollinson moved to [[Cirencester]] where in 1781 he married. In 1782 he was appointed vicar of [[Clanfield, Oxfordshire]]. At this period he published one book, and issued proposals for county histories, firstly of [[Wiltshire]] and then of Somerset. He associated with the antiquarians [[Joseph Kilner]] and [[Samuel Rudder]], and in 1784 was elected a Fellow of the [[Society of Antiquaries of London]], backed by [[Daines Barrington]], [[William Boys (surgeon)|William Boys]] and [[Edward Hasted]].<ref name =\"ODNB\"/> \n\nIn 1787 Collinson became vicar of [[Long Ashton]] and perpetual curate of [[Whitchurch, Somerset|Filton]] (''alias'' [[Whitchurch, Somerset|Whitchurch]]) in Somerset. He died at [[Hotwells, Bristol]] on 27 August 1793, and was buried at Long Ashton.<ref name =\"ODNB\"/>\n\n==History of Somerset==\nCollinson's magnum opus was his ''History and Antiquities of the County of Somerset'', which bears the date 1791 on its title pages although it did not in fact appear until 1792. \n\nThe work made use of the standard antiquarian and historical works, as the title page acknowledges, and partially included a survey by [[Edmund Rack]] of [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]]. An initial difficulty was met when the expected access to the papers of [[John Strachey (geologist)|John Strachey]] was not granted. The history is neatly organised by parish and hundred.\n\nWhile the history was heavily criticised for a lack of original research in the ''[[Gentleman's Magazine]]'' on publication,<ref>{{cite journal |author=R. P. |title=Collinson's History of Somersetshire \u2013 Farley Church |journal=The Gentleman's Magazine and Historical Chronicle |volume=64 |issue=1 |date=June 1794 |pages=497\u201399 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=al7PAAAAMAAJ&printsec=titlepage&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q&f=false }}</ref> it has subsequently been widely acknowledged as an ingenious work<ref>Felix Farley, Bristol Journal, 31 August 1793</ref> that made substantial advances in [[Domesday Book|Domesday]] nomenclature, and contains valuable records of church monument inscriptions, many of which have since been lost.<ref name=\"index\"/> That it is in large part a skilful collation and synthesis of existing historical sources, supported by some research and a deep first-hand knowledge of the county, was acknowledged by Collinson in his introduction.<ref>John Collinson, History and Antiquities of the County of Somerset, volume 1, p ix</ref> It must be remembered that Collinson was only 24 years old when he issued proposals for the history, and only 34 years old when it was published; extensive original research was neither claimed nor could reasonably be expected.<ref name=\"index\"/> \n\nCollinson's immense, historically important achievement was freely acknowledged almost a century later by [[Robert William Eyton]] who praised the historian's topographical knowledge, scholarship, utmost precision and constancy.<ref>{{cite book |first=R. W. |last=Eyton |authorlink=Robert William Eyton |title=Domesday Studies: an analysis and digest of the Somerset survey |location=London |publisher=Reeves & Turner |year=1880 |volume=1 |page=10 }}</ref> Perhaps the greatest proof of its merit is that Collinson's work has remained the standard history of Somerset for almost two centuries, and is only now being superseded by the [[Somerset Victoria County History|''Victoria County History'' of Somerset]], still in progress, of which the published volumes reference Collinson extensively throughout. \n\nA separate index volume to Collinson's history was prepared and published by the Revs. Frederic William Weaver and E. H. Bates just over a century later in 1898, which greatly facilitates the use of the work as well as updating and standardising the spelling of place names.<ref name=\"index\">{{cite book |first1=F. W. |last1=Weaver |first2=E. H. |last2=Bates |title=Index to Collinson's History of Somerset |location=Taunton |year=1898 }}</ref>\n\n==List of works==\n* ''The Beauties of British Antiquity: selected from the writings of esteemed antiquaries with notes and observations'', 1779.<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>\n* ''History and Antiquities of the County of Somerset, Collected from Authentick Records and an Actual Survey made by the late Mr Edmund Rack. Adorned with a Map of the County and Engravings of Roman and other Reliques, Town-Seals, Baths, Churches and Gentlemen's Seats'', in 3 volumes, published at Bath, Somerset, 1791:\n** Volume 1, Bath, 1791 [https://archive.org/details/historyantiqutit01colluoft]\n** Volume 2, Bath, 1791 [https://archive.org/details/historyantiqutit02colluoft]\n** Volume 3, Bath, 1791 [https://archive.org/details/historyantiqutit03colluoft]\n\n==Family==\nCollinson married Mary Hill in Cirencester on 25 March 1781.<ref>Gloucestershire Archives; Gloucester, Gloucestershire; Gloucestershire Church of England Parish Registers; Reference Number: P86/1 IN 1/3</ref> She died in 1787, leaving him a son John (b. 16 April 1782).<ref>Gloucestershire Archives; Gloucester, Gloucestershire; Gloucestershire Church of England Parish Registers; Reference Number: P86/1 IN 1/3</ref><ref name=\"ODNB\"/> He married as his second wife, Harriot Harris, on 7 July 1788 at [[Clifton, Bristol|Clifton]], believed to be a near relation of [[John Harris (Bristol)|John Harris]] who was a subscriber to the History of Somerset.<ref>Bristol Archives; Bristol, England; Bristol Church of England Parish Registers; Reference: P/StA/R/4/b</ref> There was no surviving issue of this marriage. \n\nCollinson died after a lingering illness<ref>Felix Farley, Bristol Journal, 31 August 1793</ref> on 27 August 1793. In his will, made on 10 April 1793 and proved on 8 January 1798,<ref>The National Archives, PROB 11/1300/59</ref> he left all his books, manuscripts, drawings, prints, collection of coins and antiquities to his son, John Collinson, apart from the plates engraved for the History of Somerset, in the hands of bookseller [[Charles Dilly]] and in his estimation valued between two and three hundred pounds, which were left to his mother, Elizabeth Collinson. He also left a legacy to his sister, Elizabeth Collinson, of a ring and thirty pounds to be raised from the sale of the copyright of the History of Somerset. The residue of his estate was to go to his wife. However at the administration of the will in 1798, Timothy Stevens, a bookseller of Cirencester and one of the original subscribers to the History of Somerset, came forward as a creditor and was granted all of Collinson's goods and chattels.\n\nBy 1798 Collinson's widow, Harriot, had married John Francis Hamm of [[Little Chelsea]], Middlesex, who was the chief legatee of his uncle John Manning, a wealthy West Indies merchant.<ref>Vere Langford Oliver, Caribbeana, London, 1910, vol 1</ref>. Harriot died at St Anne's Place, [[Cambridge Heath]], London, on 21 December 1846.<ref>The Gentleman's Magazine, Volume 27, 1847, p 215</ref> <ref>London Metropolitan Archives, Church of England Parish Registers, 1813-2003, p79/jn1/132</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{commons category|John Collinson}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Collinson, John}}\n[[Category:1757 births]]\n[[Category:1793 deaths]]\n[[Category:English Anglican priests]]\n[[Category:Historians of Somerset]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Society of Antiquaries of London]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Collinson_(historian)"}
{"title_page": "Varieties of Arabic", "text_new": "{{Short description|Family of language varieties}}{{About|the extant varieties of Arabic|the historical language family|Classification of Arabic languages}}\n[[File:Arabic Dialects.svg|thumb|500px|Different Arabic varieties in the [[Arab world]]]]\n\nThere are a number of [[variety (linguistics)|varieties]] (or [[Dialect|dialects]] or [[vernacular]] languages) of [[Arabic]], a [[Semitic languages|Semitic language]] within the [[Afroasiatic languages|Afroasiatic family]] originating in the [[Arabian Peninsula]]. Some organizations, such as ''[[Ethnologue]]'' and the [[International Organization for Standardization]], consider these approximately 30 different varieties to be different languages, while others, such as the [[Library of Congress]], consider them all to be dialects of Arabic.<ref>{{cite web|title=Documentation for ISO 639 identifier: ara|url=https://iso639-3.sil.org/code/ara}}</ref> Some vernacular varieties of Arabic are not comprehensible to speakers of others, as is the case of [[North Africa|North African]] vernaculars for speakers of [[Levant|Levantine]] or [[Mesopotamia|Mesopotamian]] vernaculars. Within these broad regions further and considerable geographic distinctions exist\u2014within countries, across country borders, and even between cities and villages. While vernacular varieties differ substantially, ''Fus'ha'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0641\u0635\u062d\u0649}}), the formal [[Register (sociolinguistics)|register]], is standardized and universally understood by those literate in Arabic.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kamusella|first=Tomasz|date=2017|title=The Arabic Language: A Latin of Modernity?|url=https://research-repository.st-andrews.ac.uk/bitstream/handle/10023/12443/_Journal_of_Nationalism_Memory_Language_Politics_The_Arabic_Language_A_Latin_of_Modernity.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y|journal=Journal of Nationalism, Memory & Language Politics|volume=11|issue=2|pages=117\u2013145|doi=10.1515/jnmlp-2017-0006|via=}}</ref> Western scholars make a distinction between \"[[Classical Arabic]]\" and \"[[Modern Standard Arabic]],\" while speakers of Arabic generally do not consider CA and MSA to be different languages.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kamusella|first=Tomasz|date=2017|title=The Arabic Language: A Latin of Modernity?|url=https://research-repository.st-andrews.ac.uk/bitstream/handle/10023/12443/_Journal_of_Nationalism_Memory_Language_Politics_The_Arabic_Language_A_Latin_of_Modernity.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y|journal=Journal of Nationalism, Memory & Language Politics|volume=11|issue=2|pages=117\u2013145|doi=10.1515/jnmlp-2017-0006|via=}}</ref>\n\nA major distinction exists between the widely diverging vernaculars, used for everyday speaking situations, and the formal standardized language, found mostly in writing or in prepared speech. The regionally prevalent variety is learned as the speaker's [[first language]] while the formal language is subsequently learned in school. The formal language itself varies between its modern iteration, Modern Standard Arabic (often called MSA in English) and the [[Classical Arabic]] that serves as its basis, though Arabic speakers typically do not make this distinction.\n\nThe largest differences between the classical/standard and the colloquial Arabic are the loss of [[grammatical case]]; a different and [[analytic language|strict]] word order; the loss of the previous system of [[grammatical mood]], along with the evolution of a new system; the loss of the inflected [[passive voice]], except in a few relic varieties; restriction in the use of the [[Dual (grammatical number)|dual number]] and (for most varieties) the loss of the feminine [[plural]]. Many Arabic dialects, [[Maghrebi Arabic]] in particular, also have significant [[vowel shift]]s and unusual [[consonant cluster]]s. Unlike other dialect groups, in the [[Maghrebi Arabic]] group, first-person singular verbs begin with a n- (\u0646).\n\nFurther substantial differences exist between [[Bedouin]] and [[sedentism|sedentary]] speech, the countryside and major cities, ethnic groups, religious groups, social classes, men and women, and the young and the old. These differences are to some degree bridgeable. Often, Arabic speakers can adjust their speech in a variety of ways according to the context and to their intentions\u2014for example, to speak with people from different regions, to demonstrate their level of education or to draw on the authority of the spoken language.\n\n==Language mixing and change==\n{{See also|Code-switching|Koin\u00e9 language|Pidgin|Creole language|Communication Accommodation Theory|Prestige (sociolinguistics)|Dialect leveling|}}\n\nArabic is characterized by a wide number of varieties; however, Arabic speakers are often able to manipulate the way they speak based on the circumstances. There can be a number of motivations for changing one's speech: the formality of a situation, the need to communicate with people with different dialects, to get social approval, to differentiate oneself from the listener, when citing a written text, to differentiate between personal and professional or general matters, to clarify a point, and to shift to a new topic.<ref>Bassiouney, 2009, p. 29.</ref>\n\nAn important factor in the mixing or changing of Arabic is the concept of a [[prestige dialect]]. This refers to the level of respect accorded to a language or dialect within a speech community. The formal Arabic language carries a considerable prestige in most Arabic-speaking communities, depending on the context. This is not the only source of prestige, though.<ref>Abdel-Jawad, 1986, p. 58.</ref> Many studies have shown that for most speakers, there is a prestige variety of vernacular Arabic. In Egypt, for non-Cairenes, the prestige dialect is Cairo Arabic. For Jordanian women from Bedouin or rural background, it may be the urban dialects of the big cities, especially including the capital Amman.<ref>Bassiouney, 2009, p. 19.</ref> Moreover, in certain contexts, a dialect relatively different from formal Arabic may carry more prestige than a dialect closer to the formal language\u2014this is the case in Bahrain, for example.<ref>Holes, 1983, p. 448.</ref>\n\nLanguage mixes and changes in different ways. Arabic speakers often use more than one variety of Arabic within a conversation or even a sentence. This process is referred to as [[code-switching]]. For example, a woman on a TV program could appeal to the authority of the formal language by using elements of it in her speech in order to prevent other speakers from cutting her off. Another process at work is \"leveling\", the \"elimination of very localised dialectical features in favour of more regionally general ones.\" This can affect all linguistic levels\u2014semantic, syntactic, phonological, etc.<ref>Holes 1995: 39, p. 118.</ref> The change can be temporary, as when a group of speakers with substantially different Arabics communicate, or it can be permanent, as often happens when people from the countryside move to the city and adopt the more prestigious urban dialect, possibly over a couple of generations.\n\nThis process of accommodation sometimes appeals to the formal language, but often does not. For example, villagers in central Palestine may try to use the dialect of Jerusalem rather than their own when speaking with people with substantially different dialects, particularly since they may have a very weak grasp of the formal language.<ref>Blanc, 1960, p. 62.</ref> In another example, groups of educated speakers from different regions will often use dialectical forms that represent a middle ground between their dialects rather than trying to use the formal language, to make communication easier and more comprehensible. For example, to express the [[Existential clause|existential]] \"there is\" (as in, \"there is a place where...\"), Arabic speakers have access to many different words:\n* Kuwait & Iraq: {{IPA|/aku/}}\n* Egypt, the Levant, and most of the Arabian peninsula  {{IPA|/fi\u02d0/}}\n* Tunisia: {{IPA|/fam\u02d0a/}}\n* Morocco and Algeria: {{IPA|/kajn/}}\n* Yemen: {{IPA|/peh/}}\n* Modern Standard Arabic: {{IPA|/huna\u02d0k/}}\n\nIn this case, {{IPA|/fi\u02d0/}} is most likely to be used as it is not associated with a particular region and is the closest to a dialectical middle ground for this group of speakers. Moreover, given the prevalence of movies and TV shows in Egyptian Arabic, the speakers are all likely to be familiar with it.<ref>Holes, 1995, p. 294.</ref> Iraqi ''aku'', Levantine ''f\u012bh'' and North African ''kayn'' all evolve from Classical Arabic forms (''yak\u016bn'', ''f\u012bhi'', ''k\u0101'in'' respectively), but now sound very different.\n\nSometimes a certain dialect may be associated with backwardness and does not carry mainstream prestige\u2014yet it will continue to be used as it carries a kind of covert prestige and serves to differentiate one group from another when necessary.\n\n==Regional varieties==\nThe greatest variations between kinds of Arabic are those between [[regional language]] groups. These can be divided many ways:\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Maghrebi Arabic|Maghrebi]] group\n**[[Moroccan Arabic]] (\u0627\u0644\u062f\u0627\u0631\u062c\u0629 - darija)\n**[[Tunisian Arabic]] (\u0627\u0644\u062f\u0627\u0631\u062c\u0629/\u062a\u0648\u0646\u0633\u064a - t\u016bns\u012b/derja)\n**[[Algerian Arabic]] (\u062f\u0627\u0631\u062c\u0629/\u062f\u0632\u0627\u064a\u0631\u064a - dzair\u012b/darja)\n**[[Andalusian Arabic]] (\u0623\u0646\u062f\u0644\u0633\u064a - andal\u016bs\u012b, extinct in Iberia, surviving among Andalusi communities in Morocco and Algeria)\n**[[Libyan Arabic]] (\u0644\u064a\u0628\u064a - l\u012bb\u012b)\n**[[Hassaniya Arabic]]\n**[[Saharan Arabic]]\n**[[Siculo-Arabic|Sicilian Arabic]] (\u0635\u0642\u0644\u064a - s\u012bq\u012bll\u012b, extinct in Sicily, though [[Maltese language|Maltese]] is descended from it)\n* [[Sudanese Arabic|Sudanese]] group\n**[[Sudanese Arabic]] (\u0633\u0648\u062f\u0627\u0646\u064a - s\u016bd\u0101n\u012b)\n**[[Chadian Arabic]] \n**[[Juba Arabic]]\n* [[Egyptian Arabic|Egyptian]] group\n**[[Egyptian Arabic]] (\u0645\u0635\u0631\u0649 - ma\u1e63r\u012b) \n**[[Sa'idi Arabic]] (\u0635\u0639\u064a\u062f\u0649 - \u1e63a\u02bf\u012bd\u012b)\n* [[Peninsular Arabic|Arabian Peninsula]] group\n**[[Bahrani Arabic]]\n**[[Bareqi Arabic]]\n**[[Gulf Arabic]] (\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c\u064a - \u1e35al\u012bj\u012b)\n**[[Najdi Arabic]] (\u0646\u062c\u062f\u064a - najd\u012b)\n**[[Omani Arabic]] (\u0639\u0645\u0627\u0646\u064a - \u02bfum\u0101n\u012b)\n**[[Hejazi Arabic]] (\u062d\u062c\u0627\u0632\u064a - \u1e25ij\u0101z\u012b)\n**[[Hadhrami Arabic]] (\u062d\u0636\u0631\u0645\u064a - \u1e25a\u1e0dram\u012b)\n**[[Shihhi Arabic]]\n**[[Dhofari Arabic]]\n**[[Yemeni Arabic]] (\u064a\u0645\u0646\u064a - yaman\u012b)\n**[[Tihamiyya Arabic]]\n* [[Mesopotamian Arabic|Mesopotamian]] group\n**[[Mesopotamian Arabic]]\n**[[North Mesopotamian Arabic]] (\u0645\u0648\u0635\u0644\u064a\u0629 - m\u016bsuliyya) \n**[[Baghdad Arabic]]\n**[[Baghdad Jewish Arabic]]\n**[[Judeo-Iraqi Arabic]]\n**[[Khuzestani Arabic]]\n* [[Levantine Arabic|Levantine]] group\n**[[Syrian Arabic]]\n**[[Cypriot Maronite Arabic]]\n**[[Lebanese Arabic]] (\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u0646\u064a - libn\u0113n\u012b)\n**[[Jordanian Arabic]] (\u0623\u0631\u062f\u0646\u064a - urdun\u012b)\n**[[Palestinian Arabic]] (\u0641\u0644\u0633\u0637\u064a\u0646\u064a - falas\u1e6d\u012bn\u012b)\n**[[Bedawi Arabic]] (\u0628\u062f\u0648\u064a - badaw\u012b/bdiw\u012b)\n{{Div col end}}\n\nThese large [[Regional language|regional]] groups do not correspond to borders of modern states. In the western parts of the [[Arab world]], varieties are referred to as \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0627\u0631\u062c\u0629 ''ad-d\u0101rija'', and in the eastern parts, as \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0645\u064a\u0629 ''al-\u02bf\u0101mmiyya''. Nearby varieties of Arabic are mostly [[mutual intelligibility|mutually intelligible]], but faraway varieties tend not to be. Varieties west of Egypt are particularly disparate, with Egyptian Arabic speakers claiming difficulty in understanding North African Arabic speakers, while North African Arabic speakers' ability to understand other Arabic speakers is mostly due to the widespread popularity of Egyptian Standard and to a lesser extent, the Levantine popular media, for example Syrian or Lebanese TV shows (this phenomenon is called [[Mutual intelligibility#Asymmetric intelligibility|asymmetric intelligibility]]). One factor in the differentiation of the varieties is the influence from other languages previously spoken or still presently spoken in the regions, such as [[Coptic language|Coptic]] in Egypt, [[French language|French]], [[Ottoman Turkish language|Ottoman Turkish]], [[Italian language|Italian]],  [[Spanish language|Spanish]],  [[Berber languages|Berber]], [[Punic language|Punic]] or [[Phoenician language|Phoenician]] in North Africa and the Levant,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Phoenician-language|title=Phoenician language|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref> [[Himyaritic language|Himyaritic]], [[Modern South Arabian]] and [[Old South Arabian]] in Yemen and [[Eastern Aramaic languages|Syriac Aramaic]], [[Akkadian language|Akkadian]], [[Babylonian language|Babylonian]] and [[Sumerian language|Sumerian]] in [[Mesopotamia]] ([[Languages of Iraq|Iraq]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arch.cam.ac.uk/about-us/mesopotamia/mesopotamia-history/mesopotamia-languages|title=Mesopotamian Languages \u2014 Department of Archaeology|last=bkd20@cam.ac.uk|website=www.arch.cam.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=LANGUAGES OF IRAQ, ANCIENT AND MODERN|publisher=|year=2007|isbn=978-0-903472-21-0|location=|pages=11|last1=Postgate|first1=J. N.}}</ref> Speakers of [[mutual intelligibility|mutually unintelligible]] varieties are often able to communicate by switching to [[Modern Standard Arabic]].\n\n===Examples of major regional differences===\nThe following example illustrates similarities and differences between the literary, standardized varieties, and major urban dialects of Arabic. [[Maltese language|Maltese]], a distantly related [[Siculo-Arabic]] language descended from Maghrebi Arabic is also provided.\n\n''True pronunciations differ; transliterations used approach an approximate demonstration. Also, the [[Arabic phonology|pronunciation]] of [[Modern Standard Arabic]] differs significantly from region to region.''\n<!-- please don't use digraphs (kh, sh) because they conflict with [k.h, s.h]-->\n{| class=wikitable\n! Variety\n! I [[love]] [[reading]] a lot.\n! When I went to the [[library]],\n! I only found This old [[book]].\n! I wanted to read a [[book]] about the [[history]] of [[woman|women]] in [[France]].\n|-\n! [[Modern Standard Arabic]]\n| style=\"background: #ffffe4;\" | {{lang|ar|\u0623\u0646\u0627 \u0623\u062d\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0631\u0627\u0621\u0629  \u0643\u062b\u064a\u0631\u064b\u0627}}<br> {{transl|ar|DIN|\u02beana \u02beu\u1e25ibbu\u203fl-qir\u0101\u02beata ka\u1e6f\u012br\u0101}}\n| style=\"background: #ffffe4;\" | {{lang|ar|\u0639\u0646\u062f\u0645\u0627 \u0630\u0647\u0628\u062a \u0625\u0644\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0643\u062a\u0628\u0629}}<br> {{transl|ar|DIN|\u02bfindam\u0101 \u1e0fahabtu \u02beila\u203fl-maktabah}}\n| style=\"background: #ffffe4;\" | {{lang|ar|\u0644\u0645 \u0623\u062c\u062f \u0633\u0648\u0649 \u0647\u0630\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u062a\u0627\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u062f\u064a\u0645}}<br> {{transl|ar|DIN|lam \u02bea\u01e7id siw\u0101 h\u0101\u1e0fa\u203fl-kit\u0101bi\u203fl-qad\u012bm}}\n| style=\"background: #ffffe4;\" | {{lang|ar|\u0643\u0646\u062a \u0623\u0631\u064a\u062f \u0623\u0646 \u0623\u0642\u0631\u0623  \u0643\u062a\u0627\u0628\u064b\u0627 \u0639\u0646 \u062a\u0627\u0631\u064a\u062e \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0631\u0623\u0629 \u