\u00f0a el-ketab el-\u0295at\u012bg\n| redet \u0294aqra ket\u0101b \u0295an t\u0101r\u012bx l-imrayy\u0101t eb-fransa\n|-\n! [[Gulf Arabic|Gulf (Kuwait)]]\n| \u0294\u0101na w\u0101yid \u0294a\u0127ibb il-qir\u0101\u02bea\n| lamman ri\u0127t il-maktaba\n| ma lig\u0113t \u0294illa hal kit\u0101b il-qad\u012bm\n| kint \u0294ab\u012b \u0294agra kit\u0101b \u0295an tar\u012b\u03c7 il-\u0127ar\u012bm b-faransa\n|-\n! [[Hejazi Arabic|Hejazi (Jeddah)]]\n| {{transl|acw|\u0294ana marra \u0294a\u0127ubb al-gir\u0101ya}}\n| {{transl|acw|lamma ru\u0127t al-maktaba}}\n| {{transl|acw|ma lig\u012bt \u0263\u0113r h\u0101da al-kit\u0101b al-gad\u012bm}}\n| {{transl|acw|kunt \u0294ab\u0263a \u0294a\u0261ra kit\u0101b \u0295an t\u0101r\u012bx al-\u0127ar\u012bm fi faransa}}\n|-\n! [[Yemeni Arabic|Sanaani Arabic (Sanaa)]]\n| {{transl|ayn|\u02c8\u0294ana bajn \u0294a\u02c8\u0127ibb el-ge\u02c8r\u0101je \u02c8gawi}}\n| {{transl|ayn|\u02c8\u0127\u012bn \u02c8sert sa\u02c8l\u0101 el-\u02c8maktabe}}\n| {{transl|ayn|ma le\u02c8g\u0113t-\u0283 \u02c8\u00f0ajje al-ke\u02c8t\u0101b el-ga\u02c8d\u012bm}}\n| {{transl|ayn|kont \u02c8a\u0283ti \u02c8\u0294agra ke\u02c8t\u0101b \u0295an ta\u02c8r\u012bx al-\u02c8mare wast\u02e4 fa\u02c8r\u0101nsa}}\n|-\n! [[Maltese language|Maltese]]\n| jien in\u0127obb naqra \u0127afna\n| meta mort il-librerija\n| Sibt biss dan il-ktieb il-qadim\n| Ridt naqra ktieb dwar il-\u0121rajja tan-nisa fi Franza.\n|-\n|-\n! [[Jordanian Arabic|Jordanian (Amman)]]\n| \u0294ana kt\u012br ba\u0127ebb il-qir\u0101\u0294a\n| lamma ru\u0127t \u0295al-mektebe\n| ma lag\u0113t \u0294illa hal-kt\u0101b l-gad\u012bm\n| kan beddi \u0294aqra\u0294 kt\u0101b \u0295an t\u0101r\u012bx l-mara b-faransa\n|-\n! [[Jordanian Arabic| Northern Jordanian (Irbid)]]\n| \u0294ana/\u0294ani k\u1e6f\u012br ba\u0127ebb il-qir\u0101\u0294a\n| lamma ru\u0127t \u0295al-mektebe\n| ma lag\u0113te\u0283 \u0294illa hal-kt\u0101b l-gad\u012bm\n| k\u0101n baddi \u0294agra kt\u0101b \u0295an t\u0101r\u012bx l-mara b-faransa\n|-\n! [[Syrian Arabic| Syrian (Damascus)]]\n| \u0294ana kt\u012br b\u0127ebb l-\u0294ir\u0113ye\n| lamma re\u0127t \u0295al-maktbe\n| ma l\u0294\u0113t \u0294illa hal-kt\u0113b l-\u0294d\u012bm\n| k\u0101n biddi \u0294ra kt\u0101b \u0295an t\u0101r\u012bx l-mara b-fransa\n|}\nFor the sake of comparison, consider the same sentence in German and Dutch:\n\n# German: Ich lese sehr gerne. Als ich zur Bibliothek ging, fand ich nur dieses alte Buch, obwohl ich ein Buch \u00fcber die Geschichte der Frauen in Frankreich lesen wollte.\n# Dutch: Ik lees zeer graag. Toen ik naar de bibliotheek ging, vond ik slechts dit oude boek, hoewel ik een boek over de geschiedenis van de vrouwen in Frankrijk had willen lezen.\n\nOr in Spanish and Portuguese:\n\n# Spanish (orthography): Me gusta mucho leer. Cuando fui a la biblioteca, encontr\u00e9 solamente este viejo libro. Quer\u00eda leer un libro sobre la historia de las mujeres en Francia.\n# Spanish (pronunciation, [[Valladolid]]): {{IPA-es|me \u02c8\u0263usta \u02c8mut\u0283o le\u02c8er \u2016 \u02c8kwando \u02c8fwi a la \u03b2i\u03b2ljo\u02c8teka enkon\u02c8t\u027ee sola\u02c8mente \u02c8este \u02c8\u03b2jexo \u02c8li\u03b2\u027eo \u2016 ke\u02c8\u027ei.a le\u02c8e\u027e un \u02c8li\u03b2\u027eo \u02c8so\u03b2\u027ee lajs\u02c8to\u027eja \u00f0e laz mu\u02c8xe\u027ees en \u02c8f\u027ean\u03b8ja|}}\n# Portuguese (orthography): Gosto muito de ler. Quando fui \u00e0 biblioteca, encontrei somente este velho livro. Queria ler um livro sobre a hist\u00f3ria das mulheres na Fran\u00e7a.\n# Portuguese (pronunciation, [[Rio de Janeiro]]): {{IPA-pt|\u02c8g\u0254\u0283tu \u02c8m\u0169jtu d\u0292i \u02c8le\u0281 \u2016 \u02c8kw\u0250\u0303du \u02c8fuj \u02c8a bibljo\u02c8t\u025bk\u203f\u0129k\u00f5\u02c8t\u027eej \u02ccs\u0254\u02c8m\u1ebd\u02c8t\u0283\u203fe\u0283t\u0283i \u02c8v\u025b\u028eu \u02c8liv\u027eu \u2016 ki\u02c8\u027ei.\u0250/ke\u02c8\u027ei.\u0250 \u02c8le\u027e\u203f\u0169 \u02c8liv\u027eu \u02c8sob\u027ej\u203f\u0250\u203fj\u0283\u02c8t\u0254\u027ej\u0250 d\u0250(j)\u0292 mu\u02c8\u028e\u025b\u027ei\u0292 na \u02c8f\u027e\u0250\u0303s\u0250|}}\n\nSome linguists do argue that the varieties of Arabic are different enough to qualify as separate languages in the way that Spanish and Portuguese or German and Dutch do. However, as Reem Bassiouney points out, perhaps the [[Dialect#Dialect or language|difference]] between 'language' and 'dialect' is [[Pan-Arabism|to some degree political rather than linguistic]].<ref>Bassiouney, 2009, p. 26.</ref>\n\n===Other regional differences===\n\"Peripheral\" varieties of Arabic \u2013 that is, varieties spoken in countries where Arabic is not a dominant language and a [[lingua franca]] (e.g., [[Turkey]], [[Iran]], [[Cyprus]], [[Chad]], and [[Nigeria]]) \u2013 are particularly divergent in some respects, especially in their vocabularies, since they are less influenced by classical Arabic. However, historically they fall within the same dialect classifications as the varieties that are spoken in countries where Arabic is the dominant language. Because most of these peripheral dialects are located in Muslim majority countries, they are now influenced by Classical Arabic and Modern Standard Arabic, the Arabic varieties of the Qur'an and their Arabic-speaking neighbours, respectively.\n\nProbably the most divergent non-creole Arabic variety is [[Cypriot Maronite Arabic]], a nearly extinct variety that has been heavily influenced by [[Greek language|Greek]], and written in [[Greek script|Greek]] and [[Latin script|Latin]] alphabets.\n\n[[Maltese language|Maltese]] is descended from [[Siculo-Arabic]]. Its vocabulary has acquired a large number of loanwords from [[Sicilian language|Sicilian]], [[Italian language|Italian]] and recently [[English language|English]], and it uses only a Latin-based alphabet. It is the only Semitic language among the official languages of the [[European Union]].\n\nArabic-based [[pidgin]]s (which have a limited vocabulary consisting mostly of Arabic words, but lack most Arabic morphological features) are in widespread use along the southern edge of the Sahara, and have been for a long time. In the eleventh century, the medieval geographer [[al-Bakri]] records a text in an Arabic-based pidgin, probably one that was spoken in the region corresponding to modern [[Mauritania]]. In some regions, particularly around the southern Sudan, the pidgins have [[creole language|creolized]] (see the list below).\n\nEven within countries where the official language is Arabic, different varieties of Arabic are spoken. For example, within Syria, the Arabic spoken in Homs is recognized as different from the Arabic spoken in Damascus, but both are considered to be varieties of \"Levantine\" Arabic. And within Morocco, the Arabic of the city of Fes is considered different from the Arabic spoken elsewhere in the country.\n\n==Formal and vernacular differences==\nAnother way that varieties of Arabic differ is that some are formal and others are colloquial (that is, vernacular). There are two formal varieties, or \u0627\u0644\u0644\u063a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0635\u062d\u0649 ''al-lugha(t) al-fu\u1e63\u1e25\u00e1'', One of these, known in English as ''Modern Standard Arabic'' (''MSA''), is used in contexts such as writing, broadcasting, interviewing, and speechmaking. The other, Classical Arabic, is the language of the Qur'an. It is rarely used except in reciting the Qur'an or quoting older classical texts.<ref>Bassiouney, 2009, p. 11.</ref> (Arabic speakers typically do not make an explicit distinction between MSA and Classical Arabic.) Modern Standard Arabic was deliberately developed in the early part of the 19th century as a modernized version of Classical Arabic.\n\nPeople often use a mixture of both colloquial and formal Arabic. For example, interviewers or speechmakers generally use MSA in asking prepared questions or making prepared remarks, then switch to a colloquial variety to add a spontaneous comment or respond to a question. The ratio of MSA to colloquial varieties depends on the speaker, the topic, and the situation&mdash;amongst other factors. Today even the least educated citizens are exposed to MSA through public education and exposure to mass media, and so tend to use elements of it in speaking to others.<ref>http://www.arabacademy.com/faq/arabic_language Questions from Prospective Students on the varieties of Arabic Language \u2013 online Arab Academy</ref> This is an example of what linguistics researchers call ''[[diglossia]]''. ''See [[Linguistic register]].''\n\n[[File:Arabic diglossia diagram Badawi.svg|thumb|400px|The diagram]]\nEgyptian linguist [[El-Said Badawi|Al-Said Badawi]] proposed the following distinctions between the different \"levels of speech\" involved when speakers of Egyptian Arabic switch between vernacular and formal Arabic varieties:\n* \u0641\u0635\u062d\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0631\u0627\u062b ''fu\u1e63\u1e25\u00e1 at-tur\u0101\u1e6f'', 'heritage classical': The Classical Arabic of Arab literary heritage and the Qur'an. This is primarily a written language, but it is heard in spoken form at the mosque or in religious programmes on television, but with a [[Modern Standard Arabic|modernized pronunciation]].\n* \u0641\u0635\u062d\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0635\u0631 ''fu\u1e63\u1e25\u00e1 al-\u02bfa\u1e63r'', 'contemporary classical' or 'modernized classical': This is what Western linguists call [[Modern Standard Arabic]] (MSA). It is a modification and simplification of Classical Arabic that was deliberately created for the modern age. Consequently, it includes many newly coined words, either adapted from Classical Arabic (much as European scholars during the Renaissance coined new English words by adapting words from Latin), or borrowed from foreign, chiefly European, languages. Although it is principally a written language, it is spoken when people read aloud from prepared texts. Highly skilled speakers can also produce it spontaneously, though this typically occurs only in the context of media broadcasts \u2013 particularly in [[talk show|talk]] and debate programs on pan-Arab television networks such as [[Al Jazeera]] and [[Al Arabiya]] \u2013 where the speakers want to be simultaneously understood by Arabic speakers in all the various countries where these networks' target audiences live. If highly skilled speakers use it spontaneously, it is spoken when Arabic speakers of different dialects communicate each other. Commonly used as a written language, it is found in most books, newspapers, magazines, official documents, and reading primers for small children; it is also used as another version of literary form of the Qur'an and in modernized revisions of writings from Arab literary heritage.\n* \u0639\u0627\u0645\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062b\u0642\u0641\u064a\u0646 ''\u02bf\u0101mmiyyat al-mu\u1e6faqqaf\u012bn'', 'colloquial of the cultured': This is a vernacular dialect that has been heavily influenced by MSA, i.e. [[loanword|borrowed words]] from MSA (this is similar to the literary [[Romance languages]], wherein scores of words were borrowed directly from [[Classical Latin]]); loanwords from MSA replace or are sometimes used alongside native words evolved from Classical Arabic in colloquial dialects. It tends to be used in serious discussions by well-educated people, but is generally not used in writing except informally. It includes a large number of foreign loanwords, chiefly relating to the technical and theoretical subjects it is used to discuss, sometimes used in non-intellectual topics. Because it can generally be understood by listeners who speak varieties of Arabic different from those of the speaker's country of origin, it is often used on television, and it is also becoming the language of instruction at universities.\n* \u0639\u0627\u0645\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062a\u0646\u0648\u0631\u064a\u0646 ''\u02bf\u0101mmiyyat al-mutanawwar\u012bn'' 'colloquial of the basically educated': This is the everyday language that people use in informal contexts, and that is heard on television when non-intellectual topics are being discussed. It is characterized, according to Badawi, by high levels of borrowing. Educated speakers usually code-switch between ''\u02bf\u0101mmiyyat al-mu\u1e6faqqaf\u012bn'' and ''\u02bf\u0101mmiyyat al-mutanawwar\u012bn''.\n* \u0639\u0627\u0645\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u064a\u064a\u0646 ''\u02bf\u0101mmiyyat al-\u02beummiyy\u012bn'', 'colloquial of the illiterates': This is very colloquial speech characterized by the absence of any influence from MSA and by relatively little foreign borrowing. These varieties are the almost entirely naturally evolved direct descendants of Classical Arabic.\nAlmost everyone in Egypt is able to use more than one of these levels of speech, and people often switch between them, sometimes within the same sentence. This is generally true in other Arabic-speaking countries as well.<ref>Badawi, 1973.</ref>\n\nThe spoken dialects of Arabic have occasionally been written, usually in the [[Arabic alphabet]]. Vernacular Arabic was first recognized as a written language distinct from Classical Arabic in 17th century [[Ottoman Egypt]], when the Cairo elite began to trend towards colloquial writing. A record of the Cairo vernacular of the time is found in the dictionary compiled by [[Yusuf al-Maghribi]]. More recently, many plays and poems, as well as a few other works exist in [[Lebanese Arabic]] and [[Egyptian Arabic]]; books of poetry, at least, exist for most varieties. In [[Algeria]], colloquial [[Maghrebi Arabic]] was taught as a separate subject under French colonization, and some textbooks exist. [[Mizrahi Jews]] throughout the Arab world who spoke [[Judeo-Arabic]] dialects rendered newspapers, letters, accounts, stories, and translations of some parts of their liturgy in the [[Hebrew alphabet]], adding diacritics and other conventions for letters that exist in Judeo-Arabic but not Hebrew. The [[Latin alphabet]] was advocated for [[Lebanese Arabic]] by [[Said Aql]], whose supporters published several books in his transcription. In 1944, [[Abdelaziz Pasha Fahmi]], a member of the [[Academy of the Arabic Language in Cairo|Academy of the Arabic Language]] in Egypt proposed the replacement of the [[Arabic alphabet]] with the Latin alphabet. His proposal was discussed in two sessions in the communion but was rejected, and faced strong opposition in cultural circles.<ref>Al-Sawi, 2004, p. 7</ref> The Latin alphabet is used by Arabic speakers over the [[Internet]] or for sending [[short message service|messages]] via [[cellular phone]]s when the [[Arabic alphabet]] is unavailable or difficult to use for technical reasons;<ref name=Yaghan>Yaghan, M. (2008). \"Araby: A Contemporary Style of Arabic Slang\". ''Design Issues'' 24(2): 39-52.</ref> this is also used in Modern Standard Arabic when Arabic speakers of different dialects communicate each other.\n\n==Sociolinguistic variables==\n[[Sociolinguistics]] is the study of how language usage is affected by societal factors, e.g., cultural norms and contexts (see also [[pragmatics]]). The following sections examine some of the ways that modern Arab societies influence how Arabic is spoken.\n\n===Religion===\nThe religion of Arabic speakers is sometimes involved in shaping how they speak Arabic. As is the case with other variables, religion cannot be seen in isolation. It is generally connected with the political systems in the different countries. Religion in the Arab world is not usually seen as an individual choice. Rather, it is matter of group affiliation: one is born a [[Muslim]] (and even either [[Sunni]] or [[Shiite]] among them), [[Christians|Christian]] or [[Jew]], and this becomes a bit like one's ethnicity. Religion as a sociolinguistic variable should be understood in this context.<ref>Bassiouney, 2009, p.105.</ref>\n\n[[Bahrain]] provides an excellent illustration. A major distinction can be made between the Shiite Bahraini, who are the oldest population of Bahrain, and the Sunni population that began to immigrate to Bahrain in the eighteenth century. The Sunni form a minority of the population. The ruling family of Bahrain is Sunni. The colloquial language represented on TV is almost invariably that of the Sunni population. Therefore, power, prestige and financial control are associated with the Sunni Arabs. This is having a major effect on the direction of language change in Bahrain.<ref>Holes, 1984, p.433-457.</ref>\n\nThe case of [[Iraq]] also illustrates how there can be significant differences in how Arabic is spoken on the basis of religion. Note that the study referred to here was conducted before the [[Iraq War]]. In [[Baghdad]], there are significant linguistic differences between Arabic Christian and Muslim inhabitants of the city. The Christians of Baghdad are a well-established community, and their dialect has evolved from the sedentary vernacular of urban medieval Iraq. The typical Muslim dialect of Baghdad is a more recent arrival in the city and comes from Bedouin speech instead. In Baghdad, as elsewhere in the Arab world, the various communities share MSA as a prestige dialect, but the Muslim colloquial dialect is associated with power and money, given that that community is the more dominant. Therefore, the Christian population of the city learns to use the Muslim dialect in more formal situations, for example, when a Christian school teacher is trying to call students in the class to order.<ref>Abu-Haidar, 1991.</ref>\n\n==Sedentary and nomadic differences==\nA basic distinction that cuts across the entire geography of the Arabic-speaking world is between sedentary and nomadic varieties (often misleadingly called [[Bedouin]]). The distinction stems from the settlement patterns in the wake of the Arab conquests. As regions were conquered, army camps were set up that eventually grew into cities, and settlement of the rural areas by [[nomadic]] Arabs gradually followed thereafter. In some areas, sedentary dialects are divided further into urban and rural variants.{{citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n\nThe most obvious phonetic difference between the two groups is the pronunciation of the letter <big>\u0642</big> ''[[qaaf|qaf]]'', which is pronounced as a voiced {{IPA|/\u0261/}} in the Urban varieties of the Arabian Peninsula (like the [[Hejazi Arabic|Hejazi dialect]] in the ancient urban cities of [[Mecca]] and [[Medina]]) as well as in the Bedouin dialects across all Arabic-Speaking Countries, but is voiceless mainly in the post-[[Arabization|Arabized]] Urban centers as either {{IPA|/q/}} (with {{IPA|[\u0261]}} being an [[allophone]] in few words mostly in [[Maghreb|North African]] cities) or {{IPA|/\u0294/}} (merging {{angbr|[[Q\u0101f|\u0642]]}} with {{angbr|[[Hamza|\u0621]]}}) in the urban centers of [[Egypt]] and the [[Levant]], all of which were mostly [[Arabization|Arabized]] after the [[Early Muslim conquests|Islamic Conquests]].\n\nThe other major phonetic difference is that the rural varieties preserve the [[Classical Arabic]] (CA) [[interdental]]s {{IPA|/\u03b8/}} \u062b and {{IPA|/\u00f0/}} \u0630,{{citation needed|date=August 2011}} and merge the CA emphatic sounds {{IPA|/\u026e\u02e4/}} \u0636 and {{IPA|/\u00f0\u02e4/}} \u0638 into {{IPA|/\u00f0\u02e4/}} rather than sedentary {{IPA|/d\u02e4/}}.{{citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n\nThe most significant differences between rural Arabic and non-rural Arabic are in syntax. The sedentary varieties in particular share a number of common innovations from CA.{{specify|date=April 2011}} This has led to the suggestion, first articulated by [[Charles A. Ferguson|Charles Ferguson]], that a simplified [[koin\u00e9 language]] developed in the army staging camps in Iraq, whence the remaining parts of the modern Arab world were conquered.{{citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n\nIn general the rural varieties are more conservative than the sedentary varieties and the rural varieties within the Arabian peninsula are even more conservative than those elsewhere. Within the sedentary varieties, the western varieties (particularly, [[Moroccan Arabic]]) are less conservative than the eastern varieties.{{citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n\nA number of cities in the Arabic world speak a \"Bedouin\" variety, which acquires prestige in that context.{{citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n\n==Variation==\n\n=== Writing system ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Different representations for some phonemes that did not exist in Classical Arabic\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Phoneme\n! colspan=\"10\" |Letters\n|-\n![[Moroccan Arabic|Moroccan]]\n![[Tunisian Arabic|Tunisian]]\n![[Algerian Arabic|Algerian]]\n![[Hejazi Arabic|Hejazi]]\n![[Najdi Arabic|Najdi]]\n![[Egyptian Arabic|Egyptian]]\n!Levantine\n![[Palestinian Arabic|Palestinian]]\n![[Mesopotamian Arabic|Iraqi]]\n![[Gulf Arabic|Gulf]]\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|{{IPAslink|\u0261}}\n|<big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u06ad]]}}</big> / <big>{{script/Arabic|[[Gaf|\u06af]]}}</big>\n| colspan=\"2\" |<big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u06a8]]}}</big> / <big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u06a7|\u06a7\u0640]] [[\u06a7|\u0640\u06a7\u0640]] [[\u066f|\u0640\u066f]]}}</big> / <big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u0642]]}}</big>\n| colspan=\"2\" |<big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u0642]]}}</big>\n|<big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u062c]]}}<sup>{{efn|In Egypt, when there is a need to transcribe {{IPA|/\u0292/}} or {{IPA|/d\u0361\u0292/}}, both are approximated to {{IPA|[\u0292]}} using [[\u0686]].|name=Egyptian}}</sup></big>\n|<big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u063a]]}}</big> / <big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u062c]]}}<sup>{{efn|{{IPA|/g/}} is not part of the phonemic inventory of urban Levantine dialects, including Palestinian.|name=Levantine}}</sup></big>\n|<big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u0686]]}}</big> / <big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u062c]]}}<sup>{{efn|{{IPA|/g/}} is not part of the phonemic inventory of urban Levantine dialects, including Palestinian.|name=Levantine}}</sup></big>\n|<big>{{script/Arabic|[[Gaf|\u06af]]}}</big> / <big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u0643]]}}</big>\n|<big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u0642]] / [[\u06af]]}}</big>\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|{{IPAslink|t\u0361\u0283}}\n| <big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u069c]]}}</big>\n| colspan=\"7\" |<big>{{script/Arabic|\u062a\u0634}}</big>\n| colspan=\"2\" | <big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u0686]]}}<sup>{{efn|{{IPA|/t\u0361\u0283/}} is a native phoneme/allophone only in Iraqi, Gulf and some rural Levantine dialects.|name=ch}}</sup></big>\n|-\n! colspan=\"11\" |Foreign Phonemes<big><sup>{{efn|unlike {{IPA|/g/}} and {{IPA|/t\u0361\u0283/}}, {{IPA|/p/}} and {{IPA|/v/}} never appear natively in Arabic dialects, and they are always restricted to loanwords, with their usage depending on the speaker.|name=p and v}}</sup></big>\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|{{IPAslink|p}}\n| colspan=\"10\" |<big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u067e]]}}</big> / <big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u0628]]}}</big>\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|{{IPAslink|v}}\n| colspan=\"3\" |<big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u06a5]]}}</big> / <big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u06a2]]}}</big> / <big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u0641]]}}</big>\n| colspan=\"7\" |<big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u06a4]]}}</big> / <big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u0641]]}}</big>\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Morphology and syntax===\n;All varieties, sedentary and nomadic, differ in the following ways from [[Classical Arabic]] (CA):\n* The order [[subject\u2013verb\u2013object]] may be more common than [[verb\u2013subject\u2013object]].\n* Verbal agreement between subject and object is always complete.\n** In CA, there was no number agreement between subject and verb when the subject was third-person and the subject followed the verb.\n* Loss of case distinctions (''[[\u02beI\u02bfrab]]'').\n* Loss of original mood distinctions other than the indicative and imperative (i.e., subjunctive, jussive, energetic I, energetic II).\n** The dialects differ in how exactly the new indicative was developed from the old forms. The sedentary dialects adopted the old subjunctive forms (feminine {{IPA|/i\u02d0/}}, masculine plural {{IPA|/u\u02d0/}}), while many of the Bedouin dialects adopted the old indicative forms (feminine {{IPA|/i\u02d0na/}}, masculine plural {{IPA|/u\u02d0na/}}).\n** The sedentary dialects subsequently developed new mood distinctions; see below.\n* Loss of dual marking everywhere except on nouns.\n** A frozen dual persists as the regular plural marking of a small number of words that normally come in pairs (e.g., eyes, hands, parents).\n** In addition, a productive dual marking on nouns exists in most dialects ([[Tunisian Arabic|Tunisian]] and [[Moroccan Arabic]] are exceptions). This dual marking differs syntactically from the frozen dual in that it cannot take possessive suffixes. In addition, it differs morphologically from the frozen dual in various dialects, such as [[Levantine Arabic]].\n** The productive dual differs from CA in that its use is optional, whereas the use of the CA dual was mandatory even in cases of implicitly dual reference.\n** The CA dual was marked not only on nouns, but also on verbs, adjectives, pronouns and demonstratives.\n* Development of an analytic genitive construction to rival the [[I\u1e0d\u0101fah|constructed genitive]].\n** Compare the similar development of ''[[wikt:\u05e9\u05dc|shel]]'' in [[Modern Hebrew]].\n** The Bedouin dialects make the least use of the analytic genitive. [[Moroccan Arabic]] makes the most use of it, to the extent that the constructed genitive is no longer productive, and used only in certain relatively frozen constructions.\n* The relative pronoun is no longer inflected.\n** In CA, it took gender, number and case endings.\n* Pronominal clitics ending in a short vowel moved the vowel before the consonant.\n** Hence, second singular {{IPA|/-ak/}} and {{IPA|/-ik/}} rather than {{IPA|/-ka/}} and {{IPA|/-ki/}}; third singular masculine {{IPA|/-uh/}} rather than {{IPA|/-hu/}}.\n** Similarly, the feminine plural verbal marker {{IPA|/-na/}} became {{IPA|/-an/}}.\n** Because of the absolute prohibition in all Arabic dialects against having two vowels in hiatus, the above changes occurred only when a consonant preceded the ending. When a vowel preceded, the forms either remained as-is or lost the final vowel, becoming {{IPA|/-k/}}, {{IPA|/-ki/}}, {{IPA|/-h/}} and {{IPA|/-n/}}, respectively. Combined with other phonetic changes, this resulted in multiple forms for each clitic (up to three), depending on the phonetic environment.\n** The verbal markers {{IPA|/-tu/}} (first singular) and {{IPA|/-ta/}} (second singular masculine) both became {{IPA|/-t/}}, while second singular feminine {{IPA|/-ti/}} remained. Mesopotamian dialects in southeastern Turkey are an exception for they retain the ending {{IPA|/-tu/}} for first person singular.\n** In the dialect of southern [[Nejd]] (including [[Riyadh]]), the second singular masculine {{IPA|/-ta/}} has been retained, but takes the form of a long vowel rather than a short one as in CA.\n** The forms given here were the original forms, and have often suffered various changes in the modern dialects.\n** All of these changes were triggered by the loss of final short vowels (see below).\n* Various simplifications have occurred in the range of variation in verbal paradigms.\n** Third-weak verbs with radical {{IPA|/w/}} and radical {{IPA|/j/}} (traditionally transliterated ''y'') have merged in the form I perfect tense. They had already merged in CA, except in form I.\n** Form I perfect ''{{IPA|fa\u0295ula}}'' verbs have disappeared, often merging with ''{{IPA|fa\u0295ila}}''.\n** Doubled verbs now have the same endings as third-weak verbs.\n** Some endings of third-weak verbs have been replaced by those of the strong verbs (or vice versa, in some dialects).\n\n;All dialects except some Bedouin dialects of the Arabian peninsula share the following innovations from CA:\n* Loss of the inflected passive (i.e., marked through internal vowel change) in finite verb forms.\n** New passives have often been developed by co-opting the original reflexive formations in CA, particularly verb forms V, VI and VII (In CA these were derivational, not inflectional, as neither their existence nor exact meaning could be depended upon; however, they have often been incorporated into the inflectional system, especially in more innovative sedentary dialects).\n** [[Hassaniya Arabic]] contains a newly developed inflected passive that looks somewhat like the old CA passive.\n** [[Najdi Arabic]] has retained the inflected passive up to the modern era, though this feature is on its way to extinction as a result of the influence of other dialects.\n* Loss of the indefinite {{IPA|/n/}} suffix ([[tanwiin]]) on nouns.\n** When this marker still appears, it is variously {{IPA|/an/}}, {{IPA|/in/}}, or {{IPA|/en/}}.\n** In some Bedouin dialects it still marks indefiniteness on any noun, although this is optional and often used only in oral poetry.\n** In other dialects it marks indefiniteness on post-modified nouns (by adjectives or relative clauses).\n** All Arabic dialects preserve a form of the CA adverbial accusative {{IPA|/an/}} suffix, which was originally a tanwiin marker.\n* Loss of verb form IV, the causative.\n** Verb form II sometimes gives causatives, but is not productive.\n* Uniform use of {{IPA|/i/}} in imperfect verbal prefixes.\n** CA had {{IPA|/u/}} before form II, III and IV active, and before all passives, and {{IPA|/a/}} elsewhere.\n** Some Bedouin dialects in the Arabian peninsula have uniform {{IPA|/a/}}.\n** [[Najdi Arabic]] has {{IPA|/a/}} when the following vowel is {{IPA|/i/}}, and {{IPA|/i/}} when the following vowel is {{IPA|/a/}}.\n\n;All sedentary dialects share the following additional innovations:\n* Loss of a separately distinguished feminine plural in verbs, pronouns and demonstratives. This is usually lost in adjectives as well.\n* Development of a new indicative-subjunctive distinction.\n** The indicative is marked by a prefix, while the subjunctive lacks this.\n** The prefix is {{IPA|/b/}} or {{IPA|/bi/}} in [[Egyptian Arabic]] and [[Levantine Arabic]], but {{IPA|/ka/}} or {{IPA|/ta/}} in [[Moroccan Arabic]]. It is not infrequent to encounter {{IPA|/\u0127a/}} as an indicative prefix in some Persian Gulf states; and, in South Arabian Arabic (viz. Yemen), {{IPA|/\u0295a/}} is used in the north around the San'aa region, and {{IPA|/\u0283a/}} is used in the southwest region of Ta'iz.\n** [[Tunisian Arabic]] (except some rural dialects which use the prefix {{IPA|/ta/}}), and therefore does not have this distinction, along with [[Maltese language|Maltese]] and at least some varieties of [[Algerian Arabic|Algerian]] and [[Libyan Arabic]].{{incomprehensible inline|incomplete sentence|date=October 2017}}\n* Loss of {{IPA|/h/}} in the third-person masculine enclitic pronoun, when attached to a word ending in a consonant.\n** The form is usually {{IPA|/u/}} or {{IPA|/o/}} in sedentary dialects, but {{IPA|/ah/}} or {{IPA|/ih/}} in Bedouin dialects.\n** After a vowel, the bare form {{IPA|/h/}} is used, but in many sedentary dialects the {{IPA|/h/}} is lost here as well. In Egyptian Arabic, for example, this pronoun is marked in this case only by lengthening of the final vowel and concomitant stress shift onto it, but the \"h\" reappears when followed by another suffix.\n*** ''ram\u0101'' \"he threw it\"\n*** ''marama'''h\u016b'''\u0283'' \"he didn't throw it\"\n\n;The following innovations are characteristic of many or most sedentary dialects:\n* Agreement (verbal, adjectival) with inanimate plurals is plural, rather than feminine singular or feminine plural, as in CA.\n* Development of a [[circumfix]] [[Negation in Arabic|negative marker]] on the verb, involving a prefix {{IPA|/ma-/}} and a suffix {{IPA|/-\u0283/}}.\n** In combination with the fusion of the indirect object and the development of new mood markers, this results in morpheme-rich verbal complexes that can approach [[polysynthetic language]]s in their complexity.\n** An example from [[Egyptian Arabic]]:\n*** {{IPA|/ma-bi-t-\u0261ib-u-ha-lna\u02d0-\u0283/}}\n*** [negation]-[indicative]-[2nd.person.subject]-bring-[feminine.object]-to.us-[negation]\n*** \"You (plural) aren't bringing her (them) to us.\"\n** (NOTE: Versteegh glosses {{IPA|/bi/}} as ''continuous''.)\n* In [[Egyptian Arabic|Egyptian]], [[Tunisian Arabic|Tunisian]] and [[Moroccan Arabic]], the distinction between active and passive participles has disappeared except in form I and in some Classical borrowings.\n** These dialects tend to use form V and VI active participles as the passive participles of forms II and III.\n\n;The following innovations are characteristic of [[Maghrebi Arabic]] (in [[North Africa]], west of Egypt):\n* In the imperfect, [[Maghrebi Arabic]] has replaced first person singular {{IPA|/\u0294-/}} with {{IPA|/n-/}}, and the first person plural, originally marked by {{IPA|/n-/}} alone, is also marked by the {{IPA|/-u/}} suffix of the other plural forms.\n* [[Moroccan Arabic]] has greatly rearranged the system of verbal derivation, so that the traditional system of forms I through X is not applicable without some stretching. It would be more accurate to describe its verbal system as consisting of two major types, [[triliteral]] and [[quadriliteral]], each with a mediopassive variant marked by a prefixal {{IPA|/t-/}} or {{IPA|/tt-/}}.\n** The triliteral type encompasses traditional form I verbs (strong: {{IPA|/kt\u0259b/}} \"write\"; geminate: {{IPA|/\u0283\u0259mm/}} \"smell\"; hollow: {{IPA|/bi\u0295/}} \"sell\", {{IPA|/qul/}} \"say\", {{IPA|/xaf/}} \"fear\"; weak {{IPA|/\u0283ri/}} \"buy\", {{IPA|/\u0127bu/}} \"crawl\", {{IPA|/bda/}} \"begin\"; irregular: {{IPA|/kul/}}-{{IPA|/kla/}} \"eat\", {{IPA|/ddi/}} \"take away\", {{IPA|/\u0292i/}} \"come\").\n** The quadriliteral type encompasses strong [CA form II, quadriliteral form I]: {{IPA|/s\u02e4r\u02e4f\u0259q/}} \"slap\", {{IPA|/hrr\u0259s/}} \"break\", {{IPA|/hrn\u0259n/}} \"speak nasally\"; hollow-2 [CA form III, non-CA]: {{IPA|/\u0295aj\u0259n/}} \"wait\", {{IPA|/\u0261uf\u0259l/}} \"inflate\", {{IPA|/mix\u0259l/}} \"eat\" (slang); hollow-3 [CA form VIII, IX]: {{IPA|/xt\u02e4ar\u02e4/}} \"choose\", {{IPA|/\u0127mar\u02e4/}} \"redden\"; weak [CA form II weak, quadriliteral form I weak]: {{IPA|/wrri/}} \"show\", {{IPA|/s\u02e4qs\u02e4i/}} \"inquire\"; hollow-2-weak [CA form III weak, non-CA weak]: {{IPA|/sali/}} \"end\", {{IPA|/ruli/}} \"roll\", {{IPA|/tiri/}} \"shoot\"; irregular: {{IPA|/s\u02e4if\u0259t\u02e4/}}-{{IPA|/s\u02e4af\u0259t\u02e4/}} \"send\".\n** There are also a certain number of quinquiliteral or longer verbs, of various sorts, e.g. weak: {{IPA|/pid\u02e4ali/}} \"pedal\", {{IPA|/bl\u02e4ani/}} \"scheme, plan\", {{IPA|/fanti/}} \"dodge, fake\"; remnant CA form X: {{IPA|/st\u0259\u0295m\u0259l/}} \"use\", {{IPA|/stah\u0259l/}} \"deserve\"; diminutive: {{IPA|/t-bir\u02e4\u0292\u0259z/}} \"act bourgeois\", {{IPA|/t-bizn\u0259s/}} \"deal in drugs\".\n** Note that those types corresponding to CA forms VIII and X are rare and completely unproductive, while some of the non-CA types are productive. At one point, form IX significantly increased in productivity over CA, and there are perhaps 50\u2013100 of these verbs currently, mostly stative but not necessarily referring to colors or bodily defects. However, this type is no longer very productive.\n** Due to the merging of short {{IPA|/a/}} and {{IPA|/i/}}, most of these types show no stem difference between perfect and imperfect, which is probably why the languages has incorporated new types so easily.\n\n;The following innovations are characteristic of [[Egyptian Arabic]]:\n* [[Egyptian Arabic]], probably under the influence of [[Coptic language|Coptic]], puts the demonstrative pronoun after the noun ({{IPA|/al-X da/}} \"this X\" instead of CA {{IPA|/ha\u02d0\u00f0a\u02d0 l-X/}}) and leaves [[interrogative pronoun]]s [[in situ]] rather than fronting them, as in other dialects.\n\n===Phonetics===\nWhen it comes to phonetics the Arabic dialects differ in the pronunciation of the short vowels ({{IPAslink|a}}, {{IPAslink|u}} and {{IPAslink|i}}) and a number of selected consonants, mainly {{angbr|\u0642}} {{IPA|/q/}}, {{angbr|\u062c}} {{IPA|/d\u0361\u0292/}} and the [[interdental consonant]]s {{angbr|\u062b}} {{IPA|/\u03b8/}}, {{angbr|\u0630}} {{IPA|/\u00f0/}} and {{angbr|\u0638}} {{IPA|/\u00f0\u02e4/}}, in addition to the dental {{angbr|\u0636}} {{IPA|/d\u02e4/}}.\n\n====Emphasis spreading====\nEmphasis spreading is a phenomenon where {{IPA|/a/}} is backed to {{IPA|[\u0251]}} in the vicinity of emphatic consonants. The domain of emphasis spreading is potentially unbounded; in [[Egyptian Arabic]], the entire word is usually affected, although in [[Levantine Arabic]] and some other varieties, it is blocked by {{IPA|/i/}} or {{IPAslink|j}} (and sometimes {{IPAslink|\u0283}}). It is associated with a concomitant decrease in the amount of pharyngealization of emphatic consonants, so that in some dialects emphasis spreading is the only way to distinguish emphatic consonants from their plain counterparts. It also pharyngealizes consonants between the source consonant and affected vowels, although the effects are much less noticeable than for vowels.\nEmphasis spreading does ''not'' affect the affrication of non-emphatic {{IPAslink|t}} in [[Moroccan Arabic]], with the result that these two phonemes are always distinguishable regardless of the nearby presence of other emphatic phonemes.\n\n====Consonants====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Letter\n! colspan=\"2\" |Dialect Group\n! colspan=\"4\" |Levantine\n! colspan=\"3\" |Peninsular\n! colspan=\"2\" |Mesopotamian\n! colspan=\"2\" |Nilo-Egyptian\n! colspan=\"4\" |Maghrebi\n|-\n!Old Arabic\n!Modern Standard\n!Jordanian (Amman)\n!Syrian (Damascus)\n!Lebanese (Beirut)\n!Palestinian (Jerusalem)\n!Hejazi (Urban)\n!Najdi\n(Riyadh)\n!Kuwaiti (Kuwait)\n!Iraqi (Baghdad)\n!Iraqi (Mosul)\n!Upper Egyptian (Sohag)\n!Lower Egyptian (Cairo)\n!Tunisian (Tunis)\n!Algerian (Algiers)\n!Algierian ( Oran)\n!Moroccan (Urban)\n|-\n|<big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u0642]]}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPA|/k\u02bc/}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPA|/q/}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u0261}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u0294}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u0294}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u0294}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u0261}}\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u0261}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u0261}},{{IPAblink|d\u0361\u0292}}\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u0261}},{{IPAblink|d\u0361\u0292}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|q}}</big>,<big>{{IPAblink|d\u0361\u0292}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u0261}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u0294}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|q}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|q}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|q}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|q}}</big>\n|-\n|<big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u062c]]}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPA|/g/}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPA|/d\u0361\u0292/}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d\u0361\u0292}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u0292}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u0292}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u0292}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d\u0361\u0292}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d\u0361\u0292}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d\u0361\u0292}},{{IPAblink|j}}\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d\u0361\u0292}},{{IPAblink|j}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d\u0361\u0292}},{{IPAblink|j}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u0292}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u0261}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u0292}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d\u0361\u0292}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u0292}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u0292}}</big>\n|-\n|<big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u062b]]}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPA|/\u03b8/}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPA|/\u03b8/}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u03b8}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|t}},{{IPAblink|s}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|t}},{{IPAblink|s}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|t}},{{IPAblink|s}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|t}},{{IPAblink|s}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u03b8}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u03b8}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u03b8}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u03b8}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|t}},{{IPAblink|s}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|t}},{{IPAblink|s}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u03b8}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u03b8}},{{IPAblink|t}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|t}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|t}}</big>\n|-\n|<big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u0630]]}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPA|/\u00f0/}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPA|/\u00f0/}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u00f0}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d}},{{IPAblink|z}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d}},{{IPAblink|z}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d}},{{IPAblink|z}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d}},{{IPAblink|z}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u00f0}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u00f0}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u00f0}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u00f0}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d}},{{IPAblink|z}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d}},{{IPAblink|z}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|\u00f0}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d}}</big>\n|-\n|<big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u0638]]}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPA|/\u00f0\u02e0/}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPA|/\u00f0\u02e4/}}</big>\n| rowspan=\"2\" |<big>{{IPAblink|\u00f0\u02e4}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d\u02e4}},{{IPAblink|z\u02e4}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d\u02e4}},{{IPAblink|z\u02e4}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d\u02e4}},{{IPAblink|z\u02e4}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d\u02e4}},{{IPAblink|z\u02e4}}</big>\n| rowspan=\"2\" |<big>{{IPAblink|\u00f0\u02e4}}</big>\n| rowspan=\"2\" |<big>{{IPAblink|\u00f0\u02e4}}</big>\n| rowspan=\"2\" |<big>{{IPAblink|\u00f0\u02e4}}</big>\n| rowspan=\"2\" |<big>{{IPAblink|\u00f0\u02e4}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d\u02e4}},{{IPAblink|z\u02e4}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d\u02e4}},{{IPAblink|z\u02e4}}</big>\n| rowspan=\"2\" |<big>{{IPAblink|\u00f0\u02e4}}</big>\n| rowspan=\"2\" |<big>{{IPAblink|d\u02e4}}</big>\n| rowspan=\"2\" |<big>{{IPAblink|d\u02e4}}</big>\n| rowspan=\"2\" |<big>{{IPAblink|d\u02e4}}</big>\n|-\n|<big>{{script/Arabic|[[\u0636]]}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPA|/\u026e\u02e0/}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPA|/d\u02e4/}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d\u02e4}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d\u02e4}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d\u02e4}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d\u02e4}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d\u02e4}}</big>\n|<big>{{IPAblink|d\u02e4}}</big>\n|}\nNote: most dialects of Arabic will use {{IPAblink|q}} for {{angbr|[[Q\u0101f|\u0642]]}} in learned words that are borrowed from Standard Arabic into the respective dialect or when Arabs speak Modern Standard Arabic.\n\nThe main dialectal variations in Arabic consonants revolve around the six consonants; {{angbr|[[\u01e7\u012bm|\u062c]]}}, {{angbr|[[Q\u0101f|\u0642]]}}, {{angbr|[[\u1e6e\u0101\u02be|\u062b]]}}, {{angbr|[[\u1e0e\u0101l|\u0630]]}}, {{angbr|[[\u1e0c\u0101d|\u0636]]}} and {{angbr|[[\u1e92\u0101\u02be|\u0638]]}}.\n\nClassical Arabic {{angbr|\u0642}} {{IPA|/q/}} varies widely from a dialect to another with {{IPAblink|\u0261}}, {{IPAblink|q}} and {{IPAblink|\u0294}} being the most common:\n\n* {{IPAblink|\u0261}} in most of the [[Arabian Peninsula]], [[San'ani Arabic|Northern]] and [[Hadhrami Arabic|Eastern]] Yemen and parts of Oman, Southern [[Mesopotamian Arabic|Iraq]], some parts of the Levant, [[Upper Egypt]], [[Sudan]], [[Libya]], [[Mauritania]] and to lesser extent in some parts (mostly rural) of [[Tunisia]], [[Algeria]], and [[Morocco]] but it is also used partially across those countries in some words.\n* {{IPAblink|q}} in most of Tunisia, Algeria and Morocco, [[Ta'izzi-Adeni Arabic|Southern]] and [[Tihamiyya Arabic|Western]] Yemen and parts of Oman, Northern Iraq, parts of the Levant especially [[Druze]] dialects. However, most other dialects of Arabic will use this pronunciation in learned words that are borrowed from Standard Arabic into the respective dialect.\n* {{IPAblink|\u0294}} in most of the Levant and [[Lower Egypt]], as well as some North African towns such as [[Tlemcen]] and [[Fez, Morocco|Fez]].\n\n* other variations include {{IPAblink|\u0262}} in [[Sudanese Arabic|Sudanese]] and some forms of [[Yemeni Arabic|Yemeni]], {{IPAblink|k}} In rural [[Palestinian Arabic|Palestinian]], {{IPAblink|d\u0361\u0292}} in some positions in [[Iraqi Arabic|Iraqi]] and [[Gulf Arabic]], {{IPAblink|\u0263}} or {{IPAblink|\u0281}} in some positions in [[Sudanese Arabic|Sudanese]] and consonantally in the Yemeni dialect of [[Yemeni Arabic|Yafi']], {{IPAblink|d\u0361z }} in some positions in [[Najdi Arabic|Najdi]], though this pronunciation is fading in favor of {{IPAblink|\u0261}}.\n\nClassical Arabic {{angbr|\u062c}} {{IPA|/\u025f/}} (Modern Standard {{IPA|/d\u0361\u0292/}}) varies widely from a dialect to another with {{IPAblink|d\u0361\u0292}}, {{IPAblink|\u0292}} and {{IPAblink|\u0261}} being the most common:\n\n* {{IPAblink|d\u0361\u0292}} in most of the Arabian peninsula, Algeria, Iraq, Upper Egypt, Sudan, parts of the Levant and Yemen.\n* {{IPAblink|\u0292}} in most of the [[Levant]] and [[North Africa]].\n* {{IPAblink|\u0261}} in [[Egyptian Arabic|Lower Egypt]], parts of [[Yemen]] and [[Oman]].\n* other variations include {{IPAblink|j}} in the Persian Gulf and southern Iraq and coastal [[Hadhramaut]]. {{IPA|[\u0261\u02b2]}} in some [[Arabia]]n [[Bedouin]] dialects, and parts of [[Sudan]], as the medieval [[Persia]]n linguist [[Sibawayh]] described it.\n\nClassical [[interdental consonant]]s {{angbr|\u062b}} {{IPA|/\u03b8/}} and {{angbr|\u0630}} {{IPA|/\u00f0/}} become {{IPA|/t, d/}} or {{IPA|/s, z/}} in some words in [[Egypt]], Sudan, most of the Levant, parts of the Arabian peninsula (urban [[Hejaz]] and parts of Yemen). In [[Morocco]], [[Algeria]] and other parts of [[North Africa]] they are consonantly {{IPA|/t, d/}}, but remain {{IPA|/\u03b8/}} and {{IPA|/\u00f0/}} in most of the Arabian Peninsula, Iraq, Tunisia, parts of Yemen, rural Palestinian, Eastern Libyan, and some rural [[Algerian Arabic|Algerian]] dialects. In Arabic-speaking towns of Eastern [[Turkey]], (Urfa, Siirt and Mardin) they respectively become {{IPA|/f, v/}}.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"float: right; margin:1em;\"\n|+Reflexes of Classical {{IPAslink|q}}\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:120px;\" |Place !! rowspan=\"2\" |Reflex !! style=\"width:50px;\" | {{IPA|/\u02c8qalb/}} !! style=\"width:50px;\" |{{IPA|/baqara/}} !! style=\"width:50px;\" |{{IPA|/\u02c8waqt/}} !! {{IPA|/\u02c8qa\u02d0l/}} !! style=\"width:50px;\" |{{IPA|/\u02c8qamar/}} !! style=\"width:50px;\" |{{IPA|/\u02c8qahwa/}} !! style=\"width:50px;\" |{{IPA|/qudda\u02d0m/}}\n|-\n! \"heart\" !! \"cow\" !! \"time\" !! \"said\" !! \"moon\" !! \"coffee\" !! \"in front of\"\n|-\n| [[Medina]], [[Hejazi Arabic]] || {{IPAblink|\u0261}} || galb || bagara || wagt || gaal || gamar || gahwa || guddaam\n|-\n| [[Uzbeki Arabic]] (Jugari) || {{IPAblink|q}}, occ. {{IPAblink|\u0261}} || qalb || baqara || waqt, (wa\u1e25t) || qaal || qamar || \u2014 || giddaam\n|-\n| Muslim [[Baghdad Arabic]] || {{IPAblink|\u0261}}, occ. {{IPAblink|d\u0361\u0292}} || ga\u1e37u\u1e05 || baqara || wak\u0259t || gaal || gumar || gahwa || geddaam, jiddaam\n|-\n| [[Jewish Baghdadi Arabic]] || {{IPAblink|q}}, occ. {{IPAblink|d\u0361\u0292}} || qalb || \u2014 || \u2014 || qaal || qama\u0263 || \u2014 || jeddaam\n|-\n| [[North Mesopotamian Arabic|Mosul]], [[Iraq]] || {{IPAblink|q}} || q\u028cl\u0259b || b\u028cg\u028c\u0263a || w\u028cq\u0259t || qaal || q\u028cm\u028c\u0263 || q\u028chwi || q\u0259ddaam\n|-\n| [[Anah]], [[Iraq]] || {{IPAblink|q}} or {{IPAblink|\u0261}} || qaalb || (bagra) || waqet || qaal || \u2014 || gahwa || \u2014\n|-\n| Rural Lower [[Iraqi Arabic]] || {{IPAblink|\u0261}}, occ. {{IPAblink|d\u0361\u0292}} || galub || bgura, bagra || wakit || gaal || gumar || ghawa, gahwa || jiddaam\n|-\n| [[Judeo-Iraqi Arabic]], [[Iraqi Kurdistan]] || {{IPAblink|q}} || qalb || baqa\u1e5ba || waqt, waxt || qaal || qama\u1e5b || qahwe || q\u01ddddaam\n|-\n| [[Mardin]], [[Anatolia]] || {{IPAblink|q}} || qalb || baqa\u1e5ba || waqt, waxt || qaal || qama\u1e5b || qa\u1e25we || q\u01ddddaam\n|-\n| Sheep nomads, [[Mesopotamia]], NE [[Arabian Peninsula]]\n| {{IPAblink|\u0261}}, occ. {{IPAblink|d\u0361\u0292}} || galb, galub || bgara || wagt, wakit || gaal || gumar || ghawa || jeddaam\n|-\n| Camel nomads, [[Mesopotamia]], NE [[Arabian Peninsula]]\n| {{IPAblink|\u0261}}, occ. {{IPAblink|d\u0361z}} || galb, galub || bgara || wagt, wakit || gaal || gumar || ghawa || d\u1dbb\u00f6ddaam\n|-\n| [[Aleppo]], [[Syrian Arabic|Syria]] || {{IPAblink|\u0294}} || \u02bealb || ba\u02beara || wa\u02bet || \u02beaal || \u02beamar || \u02beahwe || \u02be\u01ddddaam\n|-\n| [[Damascus]], [[Syrian Arabic|Syria]] || {{IPAblink|\u0294}} || \u02bealb || ba\u02beara || wa\u02bet || \u02beaal || \u02beamar || \u02beahwe || \u02be\u01ddddaam\n|-\n| [[Beirut]], [[Lebanese Arabic|Lebanon]] || {{IPAblink|\u0294}} || \u02bealb || ba\u02bera || wa\u02bet || \u02beaal || \u02beamar || \u02beahwe || \u02be\u01ddddeem\n|-\n| [[Jordanian Arabic|Amman, Jordan]] || {{IPAblink|\u0261}} or {{IPAblink|\u0294}}|| ga\u1e37ib or ''\u02be''alib || bagara or ba''\u02be'' ara || wag\u01ddt or wa''\u02be''\u01ddt  || gaal or ''\u02be''aal || gamar or ''\u02be''amar || gahweh or ''\u02be''ahweh || giddaam or ''\u02be''iddaam\n|-\n| [[Jordanian Arabic|Irbid, Jordan]] || {{IPAblink|\u0261}} || galib  || bagara || waket || gaal || gamar || gahwe \u2013 gahweh || giddaam\n|-\n| [[Druze|Sweida, Syria]] || {{IPAblink|q}} || qalb || baqara || \u2014 || qaal || qamar || qahwe || \u2014\n|-\n| [[Nazareth]], [[Palestinian Arabic|Israel]] || {{IPAblink|\u0294}} or {{IPAblink|k}} || \u02bealb (or kalb) || ba\u02beara (or bakara) || wa\u02bet (or wakt) || \u02beaal (or kaal) || \u02beamar (or kamar) || \u02beahwe (or kahwe) || \u02beuddaam (or kuddaam)\n|-\n| [[Jerusalem]] (urban [[Palestinian Arabic]]) || {{IPAblink|\u0294}} || \u02bealb || ba\u02beara || wa\u02bet || \u02beaal || \u02beamar || \u02beahwe || \u02beuddaam\n|-\n| [[Bir Zeit]], [[Palestinian Arabic|West Bank]] || {{IPAblink|k}} || kalb || bakara || wakt || kaal || kamar || kahwe || kuddaam\n|-\n| [[Sana\u02bda]], [[Yemeni Arabic|Yemen]] || {{IPAblink|\u0261}} || galb || bagara || wagt || gaal || gamar || gahweh || guddaam\n|-\n| [[Cairo]], [[Egyptian Arabic|Egypt]] || {{IPAblink|\u0294}} || \u02bealb || ba\u02beara || wa\u02bet || \u02beaal || \u02beamar || \u02beahwa || \u02beuddaam\n|-\n| [[Upper Egypt]], [[Sa'idi Arabic]] || {{IPAblink|\u0261}} || galb || bagara || wagt || gaal || gamar || gahwa || guddaam\n|-\n| [[Sudanese Arabic|Sudan]] || {{IPAblink|\u0261}} || galib || bagara || wagt || gaal || gamra || gahwa, gahawa || giddaam\n|-\n| [[Ouadda\u00ef Prefecture|Ouadai]], [[Chadian Arabic|Chad]] || {{IPAblink|\u0261}}, occ. {{IPAblink|q}} || \u2014 || beger || waqt || gaal || gamra || gahwa || \u2014\n|-\n| [[Benghazi]], E. [[Libyan Arabic|Libya]] || {{IPAblink|\u0261}} || ga\u1e37\u01ddb || \u01ddbg\u01dd\u0301\u1e5ba || wag\u01ddt || gaa\u1e37 || g\u01ddma\u1e5b || gahawa || giddaam\n|-\n|[[Tripoli]], [[Libya]]\n|[<nowiki/>[[g]]]\n|galb\n|bugra\n|wag\u01ddt\n|gaal\n|gmar\n|gahwa\n|giddam\n|-\n| [[Tunis]], [[Tunisian Arabic|Tunisia]] || {{IPAblink|q}}, occ. {{IPAblink|\u0261}} || qalb || bagra || waqt || qal || gamra, qamra || qahwa || qoddem\n|-\n| [[El Hamma|El Hamma de Gabes]], [[Tunisian Arabic|Tunisia]] || {{IPAblink|\u0261}} || gal<sup>a</sup>b || bagra || wagt || gal || gamra || gahwa || geddem\n|-\n| [[Marazig]], [[Tunisian Arabic|Tunisia]] || {{IPAblink|\u0261}}, occ. {{IPAblink|q}} || galab || bagra || wagt || gal || gamra || gahwa, qahwa || qoddem, geddem\n|-\n|[[Algiers]], [[Algerian Arabic|Algiers]] || {{IPAblink|q}} || q\u01ddlb || bqar || waqt || qal || qamar, gamra || qah\u01ddwa || qoddam\n|-\n|[[S\u00e9tif Province|S\u00e9tif]], [[Algeria]]|| {{IPAblink|\u0261}} || g\u01ddlb || bagra || waqt  || gal || gmar || qahwa  || guddam\n|-\n| [[Jijel Arabic]] ([[Algeria]]) || {{IPAblink|k}} || k\u01ddlb || bekra || w\u01ddkt || kal || km\u01ddr || kahwa || k\u01ddddam\n|-\n| [[Rabat]], [[Moroccan Arabic|Morocco]] || {{IPAblink|q}}, {{IPAblink|\u0261}} || q\u01ddlb || bgar || waqt || gal || qamar, gamra || qah\u01ddwa || q\u01ddddam, g\u01ddddam\n|-\n| [[Casablanca]], [[Moroccan Arabic|Morocco]] || {{IPAblink|q}}, {{IPAblink|\u0261}}, occ. {{IPAblink|\u0261}} || q\u01ddlb || bgar || waqt || gal || q\u01ddmr, gamra || qah\u01ddwa || qoddam\n|-\n| North [[Tangier]], [[Moroccan Arabic|Morocco]] || {{IPAblink|q}} || q\u01ddlb ||bqar || waqt, || qal || g\u01ddmra || qah\u01ddwa || qoddam\n|-\n| [[Jewish Moroccans]] ([[Judeo-Arabic]]) || {{IPAblink|q}} || q\u01ddlb || bqar || w\u01ddqt || qal || qm\u01ddr || q\u01ddhwa || q\u01ddddam\n|-\n| [[Maltese language|Maltese]] || {{IPAblink|\u0294}}  <small>(written [[q]])</small>  || qalb || baqra || waqt || qal || qamar || \u2014 || quddiem\n|-\n| [[Cypriot Maronite Arabic]] || {{IPAblink|k}} occ. {{IPAblink|x}} || kalp || pakar || oxt || kal || kamar || \u2014 || kint\u00e1m\n|-\n| [[Andalusian Arabic]] (low register) || {{IPAblink|k}} || kalb || bakar || wakt || \u2014 || kamar || \u2014 || kudd\u00edm\n|-\n|}\n* \n* CA {{IPAslink|\u0294}} is lost.\n** When adjacent to vowels, the following simplifications take place, in order:\n*** V<sub>1</sub>\u0294V<sub>2</sub> \u2192 V\u0304 when V<sub>1</sub> = V<sub>2</sub>\n*** a\u0294i a\u0294w \u2192 aj aw\n*** i\u0294V u\u0294V \u2192 ijV uwV\n*** V\u0294C \u2192 V\u0304C\n*** Elsewhere, {{IPA|/\u0294/}} is simply lost.\n** In CA and [[Modern Standard Arabic]] (MSA), {{IPAslink|\u0294}} is still pronounced.\n** Because this change had already happened in Meccan Arabic at the time the [[Qur'an]] was written, it is reflected in the orthography of written Arabic, where a diacritic known as [[hamza]]h is inserted either above an ''\u02bealif'', ''w\u0101w'' or ''y\u0101\u02be'', or \"on the line\" (between characters); or in certain cases, a diacritic \u02bealif maddah (\" \u02bealif\") is inserted over an ''\u02bealif''. (As a result, proper spelling of words involving {{IPAslink|\u0294}} is probably one of the most difficult issues in Arabic orthography. Furthermore, actual usage is in many circumstances.{{incomprehensible inline|date=October 2017}})\n** Modern dialects have smoothed out the morphophonemic variations, typically by losing the associated verbs or moving them into another paradigm (for example, {{IPA|/qara\u0294/}} \"read\" becomes {{IPA|/qara/}} or {{IPA|/\u0294ara/}}, a third-weak verb).\n** {{IPAslink|\u0294}} has reappeared medially in various words due to borrowing from CA. (In addition, {{IPAslink|q}} has become {{IPAblink|\u0294}} in many dialects, although the two are marginally distinguishable in [[Egyptian Arabic]], since words beginning with original {{IPAslink|\u0294}} can elide this sound, whereas words beginning with original {{IPAslink|q}} cannot.)\n* CA {{IPAslink|k}} often becomes {{IPAblink|t\u0361\u0283}} in the Persian Gulf, Iraq, some Rural Palestinian dialects and in some [[Bedouin]] dialects when adjacent to an original {{IPA|/i/}}, particularly in the second singular feminine enclitic pronoun, where {{IPAblink|t\u0361\u0283}} replaces Classical {{IPA|/ik/}} or {{IPA|/ki/}}). In a very few Moroccan varieties, it affricates to {{IPA|/k\u0361\u0283/}}. Elsewhere, it remains {{IPAblink|k}}.\n* CA {{IPAslink|r}} is pronounced {{IPAblink|\u0280}} in a few areas: [[Mosul]], for instance, and the Jewish variety in [[Algiers]]. In all of northern Africa, a phonemic distinction has emerged between plain {{IPAblink|r}} and emphatic {{IPA|[r\u02e4]}}, thanks to the merging of short vowels.\n* CA {{IPAslink|t}} (but not emphatic CA {{IPA|/t\u02e4/}}) is affricated to {{IPAblink|t\u0361s}} in [[Moroccan Arabic]]; this is still distinguishable from the sequence {{IPA|[ts]}}.\n* CA {{IPAslink|\u0295}}) is pronounced in [[Iraqi Arabic]] and [[Kuwaiti Arabic]] with glottal closure: {{IPA|[\u0294\u02e4]}}. In some varieties {{IPAslink|\u0295}} is devoiced to {{IPAblink|\u0127}} before {{IPAslink|h}}, for some speakers of Cairene Arabic {{IPA|/bita\u0295ha/}} \u2192 {{IPA|/bita\u0127\u0127a/}} (or {{IPA|/bita\u0295\u031e\u0127a/}}) \"hers\". The residue of this rule applies also in the Maltese language, where neither etymological {{IPAslink|h}} nor {{IPAslink|\u0295}} are pronounced as such, but give {{IPAblink|\u0127}} in this context: ''tag\u0127ha'' {{IPA|[ta\u0127\u0127a]}} \"hers\".\n* The nature of \"emphasis\" differs somewhat from variety to variety. It is usually described as a concomitant [[pharyngealization]], but in most sedentary varieties is actually [[velarization]], or a combination of the two. (The phonetic effects of the two are only minimally different from each other.) Usually there is some associated lip rounding; in addition, the stop consonants {{IPAslink|t}} and {{IPAslink|d}} are dental and lightly aspirated when non-emphatic, but alveolar and completely unaspirated when emphatic.\n* CA {{IPAslink|r}} is also in the process of splitting into emphatic and non-emphatic varieties, with the former causing emphasis spreading, just like other emphatic consonants. Originally, non-emphatic {{IPAblink|r}} occurred before {{IPA|/i/}} or between {{IPA|/i/}} and a following consonant, while emphatic {{IPA|[r\u02e4]}} occurred mostly near {{IPAblink|\u0251}}.\n** To a large extent, Western Arabic dialects reflect this, while the situation is rather more complicated in [[Egyptian Arabic]]. (The allophonic distribution still exists to a large extent, although not in any predictable fashion; nor is one or the other variety used consistently in different words derived from the same root. Furthermore, although derivational suffixes (in particular, relational {{IPA|/-i/}} and {{IPA|/-ijja/}}) affect a preceding {{IPA|/r/}} in the expected fashion, inflectional suffixes do not).\n* Certain other consonants, depending on the dialect, also cause pharyngealization of adjacent sounds, although the effect is typically weaker than full emphasis spreading and usually has no effect on more distant vowels.\n** The velar fricative {{IPAslink|x}} and the uvular consonant {{IPAslink|q}} often cause partial backing of adjacent {{IPA|/a/}} (and  of {{IPA|/u/}} and {{IPA|/i/}} in [[Moroccan Arabic]]). For [[Moroccan Arabic]], the effect is sometimes described as half as powerful as an emphatic consonant, as a vowel with uvular consonants on both sides is affected similarly to having an emphatic consonant on one side.\n** The pharyngeal consonants {{IPAslink|\u0127}} and {{IPAslink|\u0295}} cause no emphasis spreading and may have little or no effect on adjacent vowels. In [[Egyptian Arabic]], for example, {{IPA|/a/}} adjacent to either sound is a fully front {{IPAblink|\u00e6}}. In other dialects, {{IPAslink|\u0295}} is more likely to have an effect than {{IPAslink|\u0127}}.\n** In some [[Gulf Arabic]] dialects, {{IPAslink|w}} and/or {{IPAslink|l}} causes backing.\n** In some dialects, words such as {{lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647}} {{IPA|/a\u026b\u026ba\u02d0/}} ''{{transl|ar|DIN|All\u0101h}}'' has backed {{IPAblink|\u0251}}'s and in some dialects also velarized {{IPA|/l/}}.\n\n====Vowels====\n* Classical Arabic short vowels {{IPA|/a/}}, {{IPA|/i/}} and {{IPA|/u/}} undergo various changes.\n** Original final short vowels are mostly deleted.\n** Many [[Levantine Arabic]] dialects merge {{IPA|/i/}} and {{IPA|/u/}} into a phonemic {{IPAslink|\u0259}} except when directly followed by a single consonant; this sound may appear allophonically as {{IPA|/i/}} or {{IPA|/u/}} in certain phonetic environments.\n** [[Maghreb]] dialects merge {{IPA|/a/}} and {{IPA|/i/}} into {{IPAslink|\u0259}}, which is deleted when unstressed. Tunisian maintains this distinction, but deletes these vowels in non-final open syllables.\n** [[Moroccan Arabic]], under the strong influence of [[Berber languages|Berber]], goes even further. Short {{IPA|/u/}} is converted to labialization of an adjacent velar, or is merged with {{IPAslink|\u0259}}. This schwa then deletes everywhere except in certain words ending {{IPA|/-CC\u0259C/}}.\n*** The result is that there is no distinction between short and long vowels; borrowings from CA have \"long\" vowels (now pronounced half-long) uniformly substituted for original short and long vowels.\n*** This also results in consonant clusters of great length, which are (more or less) syllabified according to a sonority hierarchy. For some subdialects, in practice, it is very difficult to tell where, if anywhere, there are syllabic peaks in long consonant clusters in a phrase such as {{IPA|/xs\u02e4s\u02e4k tktbi/}} \"you (fem.) must write\". Other dialects, in the North, make a clear distinction; they say /x\u0259ss\u0259k t\u0259kt\u0259b/ \"you want to write\", and not */x\u0259ssk \u0259tk\u0259tb/.\n*** In [[Moroccan Arabic]], short {{IPA|/a/}} and {{IPA|/i/}} have merged, obscuring the original distribution. In this dialect, the two varieties have completely split into separate phonemes, with one or the other used consistently across all words derived from a particular root except in a few situations.\n**** In [[Moroccan Arabic]], the allophonic effect of emphatic consonants is more pronounced than elsewhere.\n**** Full {{IPA|/a/}} is affected as above, but {{IPA|/i/}} and {{IPA|/u/}} are also affected, and are  to {{IPAblink|e}} and {{IPAblink|o}}, respectively.\n**** In some varieties, such as in [[Marrakesh]], the effects are even more extreme (and complex), where both high-mid and low-mid allophones exist ({{IPAblink|e}} and {{IPAblink|\u025b}}, {{IPAblink|o}} and {{IPAblink|\u0254}}), in addition to front-rounded allophones of original {{IPA|/u/}} ({{IPAblink|y}}, {{IPAblink|\u00f8}}, {{IPAblink|\u0153}}), all depending on adjacent phonemes.\n**** On the other hand, emphasis spreading in [[Moroccan Arabic]] is less pronounced than elsewhere; usually it only spreads to the nearest full vowel on either side, although with some additional complications.\n**{{IPA|/i~\u026a/}} and {{IPA|/u~\u028a/}} in CA completely become {{IPA|/e/}} and {{IPA|/o/}} respectively in some other particular dialects.\n** In [[Egyptian Arabic]] and [[Levantine Arabic]], short {{IPA|/i/}} and {{IPA|/u/}} are elided in various circumstances in unstressed syllables (typically, in open syllables; for example, in Egyptian Arabic, this occurs only in the middle vowel of a VCVCV sequence, ignoring word boundaries). In Levantine, however, clusters of three consonants are almost never permitted. If such a cluster would occur, it is broken up through the insertion of {{IPAslink|\u0259}}{{spaced ndash}}between the second and third consonants in Egyptian Arabic, and between the first and second in [[Levantine Arabic]].\n* CA long vowels are shortened in some circumstances.\n** Original final long vowels are shortened in all dialects.\n** In [[Egyptian Arabic]] and [[Levantine Arabic]], unstressed long vowels are shortened.\n** [[Egyptian Arabic]] also cannot tolerate long vowels followed by two consonants, and shortens them. (Such an occurrence was rare in CA, but often occurs in modern dialects as a result of elision of a short vowel.)\n* In most dialects, particularly sedentary ones, CA {{IPA|/a/}} and {{IPA|/a\u02d0/}} have two strongly divergent allophones, depending on the phonetic context.\n** Adjacent to an emphatic consonant and to {{IPAslink|q}} (but not usually to other sounds derived from this, such as {{IPAslink|\u0261}} or {{IPAslink|\u0294}}), a back variant {{IPAblink|\u0251}} occurs; elsewhere, a strongly fronted variant {{IPAblink|\u00e6}}~{{IPAblink|\u025b}} is used.\n** The two allophones are in the process of splitting phonemically in some dialects, as {{IPAblink|\u0251}} occurs in some words (particularly foreign borrowings) even in the absence of any emphatic consonants anywhere in the word. (Some linguists have postulated additional emphatic phonemes in an attempt to handle these circumstances; in the extreme case, this requires assuming that '''every''' phoneme occurs doubled, in emphatic and non-emphatic varieties. Some have attempted to make the vowel allophones autonomous and eliminate the emphatic consonants as phonemes. Others have asserted that emphasis is actually a property of syllables or whole words rather than of individual vowels or consonants. None of these proposals seems particularly tenable, however, given the variable and unpredictable nature of emphasis spreading.)\n** Unlike other Arabic varieties, [[Hejazi Arabic]] did not develop allophones of the vowels /a/ and /a\u02d0/, and both are pronounced as {{IPAblink|a}} or {{IPAblink|\u00e4}}.\n* CA diphthongs {{IPA|/aj/}} and {{IPA|/aw/}} have become {{IPAblink|e\u02d0}} or {{IPAblink|e\u031e\u02d0}} and {{IPAblink|o\u02d0}} or {{IPAblink|o\u031e\u02d0}} (but merge with original {{IPA|/i\u02d0/}} and {{IPA|/u\u02d0/}} in [[Maghreb]] dialects, which is probably a secondary development). The diphthongs are maintained in [[Maltese language|the Maltese language]] and some urban Tunisian dialects, particularly that of [[Sfax]], while {{IPAblink|e\u02d0}} and {{IPAblink|o\u02d0}} also occur in some other Tunisian dialects, such as [[Monastir, Tunisia|Monastir]].\n* The placement of the stress accent is extremely variable between varieties; nowhere is it phonemic.\n** Most commonly, it falls on the last syllable containing a long vowel, or a short vowel followed by two consonants; but never farther from the end than the third-to-last syllable. This maintains the presumed stress pattern in CA (although there is some disagreement over whether stress could move farther back than the third-to-last syllable), and is also used in [[Modern Standard Arabic]] (MSA).\n*** In CA and MSA, stress cannot occur on a final long vowel; however, this does not result in different stress patterns on any words, because CA final long vowels are shortened in all modern dialects, and any current final long vowels are secondary developments from words containing a long vowel followed by a consonant.\n** In [[Egyptian Arabic]], the rule is similar, but stress falls on the second-to-last syllable in words of the form ...VCCVCV, as in {{IPA|/mak\u02c8taba/}}.\n** In [[Maghrebi Arabic]], stress is final in words of the (original) form CaCaC, after which the first {{IPA|/a/}} is elided. Hence {{lang|ar|\u062c\u064e\u0628\u064e\u0644}} ''{{transl|ar|DIN|\u01e7abal}}'' \"mountain\" becomes {{IPA|[\u02c8\u0292b\u0259l]}}.\n** In [[Moroccan Arabic]], phonetic stress is often not recognizable.\n\n==Classification==\n\n===Pre-Islamic varieties===\nPrior to the spread of Classical Arabic with Islam, the Arabian peninsula was linguistically diverse. Old Arabic developed among varieties of Central Semitic spoken in the northern and central peninsula, most of which were written with [[Ancient North Arabian]] alphabets. Northern Old Arabic, including Safaitic and Hismaic, is found in inscriptions across a wide swath of the Levant from Syria to northern Saudi Arabia.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Al-Jallad|first=Ahmad|title=Al-Jallad. 2018. What is Ancient North Arabian?|url=https://www.academia.edu/33917069|journal=Re-engaging Comparative Semitic and Arabic Studies Edited by Daniel Birnstiel and Na'ama Pat-El; Harrassowitz Verlag . Wiesbaden|language=en}}</ref>  In the Hijaz, [[Old Hijazi]], the language of the [[Quran|Qur'anic]] consonantal text, was spoken alongside the oasis language Dadanitic and at least four undeciphered varieties jointly referred to as Thamudic. The spoken language of the [[Nabataean Kingdom|Nabataean kingdom]] was also a form of Arabic.\n\n*[[Ancient North Arabian]]<ref>{{cite conference|last=Macdonald|first=M. C. A.|date=2000|title=Reflections on the linguistic map of pre-Islamic Arabia|url=https://www.academia.edu/4421909|volume=11|accessdate=28 July 2014|booktitle=Arabian Archaeology and Epigraphy}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|chapter-url=https://www.academia.edu/4421414|title=The Cambridge Encyclopedia of the World's Languages|last=Macdonald|first=M. C. A.|date=2004|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=0-521-56256-2|editor1-last=Woodard|editor1-first=Roger D.|pages=488\u2013533|chapter=Ancient North Arabian}}</ref>\n**Oasis North Arabian\n***Dumaitic\n***[[Dadanitic]]\n***Dispersed Oasis North Arabian\n**[[Hasaitic dialect|Hasaitic]]\n**[[Thamudic language|Thamudic]] B, C, D, and F (?)\n*[[Old Arabic]]\n**[[Safaitic dialect|Safaitic]]\n**[[Hismaic]]\n**[[Nabataean Arabic]]\n**[[Old Hijazi]]\n***[[Classical Arabic]]\n\nNote: The oasis language [[Taymanitic]] was formerly classified as a variety of Arabic but is now considered closer to [[Northwest Semitic]] due to its characteristic sound changes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kootstra|first=Fokelien|title=The Language of the Taymanitic Inscriptions and its Classification|url=https://www.academia.edu/27953337|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Modern varieties===\n\n====Northern varieties====\nNorthern varieties are influenced by the [[Aramaic language]] and to a lesser extent, the [[Turkish language]] and [[Greek language]].\n* [[Levantine Arabic]]\n** [[North Levantine Arabic]]\n*** [[Syrian Arabic]]\n*** [[Lebanese Arabic]]\n** [[South Levantine Arabic]]\n*** [[Jordanian Arabic]]\n*** [[Palestinian Arabic]]\n** [[Cypriot Maronite Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=acy acy])\n** [[Bedawi Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=avl avl])\n\n====Eastern Varieties====\nEastern Varieties are influenced by the [[Aramaic language]], [[Turkish language]], and [[Iranian languages]] like the [[Kurdish languages]] and [[Persian language]].\n* [[Mesopotamian Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=acm acm])\n** ''gelet'' varieties\n*** [[Baghdad Arabic]]\n*** [[Khuzestani Arabic]]\n** ''qeltu'' varieties\n*** [[North Mesopotamian Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=ayp ayp])\n\n====Central Varieties====\nCentral Varieties are influenced by the [[Coptic language]] and to a lesser extent the [[Nubian language]] and [[Italian language]].\n* [[Egyptian Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=arz arz])\n* [[Sa\u02bdidi Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=aec aec])\n* [[Sudanese Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=apd apd])\n\n====Western Varieties====\nWestern varieties are influenced by the [[Berber languages]], [[Punic language|Punic]] or [[Phoenician language|Phoenician]] and by [[Romance languages]].\n* [[Maghrebi Arabic]]\n** [[Koin\u00e9 language|Koines]]\n*** [[Moroccan Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=ary ary])\n*** [[Algerian Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=arq arq])\n*** [[Tunisian Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=aeb aeb])\n*** [[Libyan Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=ayl ayl])\n** Fully pre-Hilalian\n*** [[Jebli Arabic]]\n*** [[Jijel Arabic]]\n*** [[Siculo-Arabic]] (language extinct, but not family)\n**** [[Maltese language]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=mlt mlt])\n** Bedouin\n*** [[Saharan Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=aao aao])\n*** [[Hassaniya Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=mey mey])\n* [[Andalusian Arabic]] (ISO 693-3: [http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=xaa xaa]), extinct\n\n====Southern Varieties====\nSouthern Varieties are slightly influenced by the [[Persian language|Persian]] and other [[South Asian]] languages.\n* [[Peninsular Arabic]]\n** [[Gulf Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=afb afb])\n** [[Bahrani Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=abv abv])\n** [[Najdi Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=ars ars])\n** [[Hijazi Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=acw acw])\n\n====Far Southern Varieties====\nFar Southern Varieties are influenced by [[South Semitic languages]] and to a lesser extent various [[South Asian]] and [[Southeast Asian]] languages.\n* [[Yemeni Arabic]]\n** [[Hadhrami Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=ayh ayh])\n** [[San\u02bdani Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=ayn ayn])\n** [[Ta\u02bdizzi-Adeni Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=acq acq])\n** [[Dhofari Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=adf adf])\n* [[Omani Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=acx acx])\n* [[Shihhi Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=ssh ssh])\n\n====Peripheries====\n* [[Central Asian Arabic]]\n** [[Tajiki Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=abh abh])\n** [[Uzbeki Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=auz auz])\n* [[Shirvani Arabic]] (extinct)\n* [[Chadian Arabic]] (Baggara, Shuwa Arabic) (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=shu shu])\n* [[Nigerian Arabic]]\n* [[Khuzestani Arabic]]\n\n====Jewish varieties====\nJewish varieties are influenced by the [[Hebrew]] and [[Aramaic]] languages. Though they have features similar to each other, they are not a homogeneous unit and still belong philologically to the same family groupings as their non-Judeo counterpart varieties. \n* [[Judeo-Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=jrb jrb])\n** [[Judeo-Iraqi Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=yhd yhd])\n*** [[Baghdad Arabic (Jewish)|Judeo-Baghdadi Arabic]]\n** [[Judeo-Moroccan Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=aju aju])\n** [[Judeo-Tripolitanian Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=yud yud])\n** [[Judeo-Tunisian Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=ajt ajt])\n** [[Judeo-Yemeni Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=jye jye])\n\n====Creoles====\n* [[Nubi language|Nubi]]\n* [[Juba Arabic]]\n\n====Pidgins====\n* [[Maridi Arabic]]\n* [[Turku Arabic]]\n\n====Varieties identified with countries====\n* [[Algerian Arabic]]\n* [[Bahrani Arabic]]\n* [[Chadian Arabic]]\n* [[Egyptian Arabic]]\n* [[Emirati Arabic]]\n* [[Iraqi Arabic]]\n* [[Jordanian Arabic]]\n* [[Kuwaiti Arabic]]\n* [[Lebanese Arabic]]\n* [[Libyan Arabic]]\n* [[Hassaniya Arabic]] (Mauritanian Arabic)\n* [[Moroccan Arabic]]\n* [[Nigerian Arabic]]\n* [[Omani Arabic]]\n* [[Palestinian Arabic]]\n* [[Qatari Arabic]]\n* [[Sahrawi Arabic]]\n* [[Somali Arabic]]\n* [[Sudanese Arabic]]\n* [[Syrian Arabic]]\n* [[Tunisian Arabic]]\n* [[Yemeni Arabic]]\n\n====Diglossic variety====\n* [[Modern Standard Arabic]] (ISO 639-3:[http://www.sil.org/iso639-3/documentation.asp?id=arb arb])\n\n==See also==\n* [[Diglossia#Arabic|Arabic diglossia]]\n* [[Arabic (disambiguation)]]\n* [[International Association of Arabic Dialectology (AIDA)]]\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* Abdel-Jawad, H. (1986). 'The emergence of a dialect in Jordanian urban centres.' ''International Journal of the Sociology of Language'' 61.\n* Abu-Haidar, F. (1991). ''Christian Arabic of Baghdad'', Weisbaden: Otto Harasowitz.\n* Abu-Melhim, A. R. (1991). 'Code-switching and accommodation in Arabic.' ''Perspectives on Arabic Linguistics.''\n* Al-Sawi, M. (5..4). 'Writing Arabic with Roman letters.' https://www.academia.edu/843265/writing_Arabic_in_the_Latin_letters._\n* Badawi, S.A. (1973). Mustaway\u0101t al-'Arab\u012byah al-mu'\u0101\u1e63irah f\u012b Mi\u1e63r: Ba\u1e25th f\u012b 'al\u0101qat al-lughah bi-al-\u1e25a\u1e0d\u0101rah, Cairo: D\u0101r al-Ma'\u0101rif.\n* Bassiouney, Reem (2006). ''Functions of code-switching in Egypt: Evidence from monologues'', Leiden: Brill.\n* Bassiouney, Reem (2009). ''Arabic Sociolinguistics'', Washington, D.C.: Georgetown University Press.\n* Blanc, D. (1960) 'Style vari